# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: jet-engine-performance
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] An **afterburner** (or **reheat** in British English) is an additional combustion component used on some jet engines, mostly those on military supersonic aircraft.
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] Its purpose is to increase thrust, usually for supersonic flight, takeoff, and combat.
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] The afterburning process injects additional fuel into a combustor ("burner") in the jet pipe behind (i.e., "after") the turbine, "reheating" the exhaust gas.
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] Afterburning significantly increases thrust and is used as an alternative to a larger, heavier engine.
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] However, it increases fuel consumption and decreases fuel efficiency, which limits its use to short periods.
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] This aircraft application of "reheat" contrasts with the meaning and implementation of "reheat" applicable to gas turbines driving electrical generators and which reduces fuel consumption.
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] Jet engines are referred to as operating *wet* when afterburning and *dry* when not.
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] An engine producing maximum thrust wet is at *maximum power,* while an engine producing maximum thrust dry is at *military power*.
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] The first jet engine with after-burner was the E variant of the Jumo 004.
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] Jet-engine thrust is an application of Newton's reaction principle, in which the engine generates thrust because it increases the momentum of the air passing through it.
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] Thrust depends on two things: the velocity of the exhaust gas and the mass of the gas exiting the nozzle.
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] A jet engine can produce more thrust by either accelerating the gas to a higher velocity or ejecting a greater mass of gas from the engine.
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] Designing a basic turbojet engine around the second principle produces the turbofan engine, which creates slower gas, but more of it.
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] Turbofans are highly fuel efficient and can deliver high thrust for long periods of time, but the design tradeoff is a large size relative to the power output.
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] Generating increased power with a more compact engine for short periods can be achieved using an afterburner.
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] The afterburner increases thrust primarily by accelerating the exhaust gas to a higher velocity.
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] The following values and parameters are for an early jet engine, the Pratt & Whitney J57, stationary on the runway, and illustrate the high values of afterburner fuel flow, gas temperature and thrust compared to those for the engine operating within the temperature limitations for its turbine.
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] The highest temperature in the engine (about 3,700 °F (2,040 °C) occurs in the combustion chamber, where fuel is burned (at an approximate rate of 8,520 lb/h (3,860 kg/h)) in a relatively small proportion of the air entering the engine.
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] The combustion products have to be diluted with air from the compressor to bring the gas temperature down to a specific value, known as the Turbine Entry Temperature (TET) (1,570 °F (850 °C)), which gives the turbine an acceptable life.
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] Having to reduce the temperature of the combustion products by a large amount is one of the primary limitations on how much thrust can be generated (10,200 lbf (45,000 N)).
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] The gas temperature decreases as it passes through the turbine (to 1,013 °F (545 °C)).
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] The afterburner combustor reheats the gas, but to a much higher temperature (2,540 °F (1,390 °C)) than the TET (1,570 °F (850 °C)).
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] As a result of the temperature rise in the afterburner combustor, the gas is accelerated, firstly by the heat addition, known as Rayleigh flow, then by the nozzle to a higher exit velocity than that which occurs without the afterburner.
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] The mass flow is also slightly increased by the addition of the afterburner fuel.
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] The thrust with afterburning is 16,000 lbf (71,000 N).
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] The visible exhaust may show *shock diamonds*, which are caused by shock waves formed due to slight differences between ambient pressure and the exhaust pressure.
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] This interaction causes oscillations in the exhaust jet diameter over a short distance and causes visible banding where pressure and temperature are highest.
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] Thrust may be increased by burning fuel in a turbofan's cold bypass air, instead of the mixed cold and hot flows as in most afterburning turbofans.
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] An early augmented turbofan, the Pratt & Whitney TF30, used separate burning zones for the bypass and core flows with three of seven concentric spray rings in the bypass flow.
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] In comparison, the afterburning Rolls-Royce Spey used a twenty chute mixer before the fuel manifolds.
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] Plenum chamber burning (PCB) was partially developed for the vectored thrust Bristol Siddeley BS100 engine for the Hawker Siddeley P.1154 until the program was cancelled in 1965.
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] The cold bypass and hot core flows were split between two pairs of nozzles, front and rear, in the same manner as the Rolls-Royce Pegasus, and fuel was burned in the fan air before it left the front nozzles.
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] It would have given greater thrust for take-off and supersonic performance in an aircraft similar to, but bigger than, the Hawker Siddeley Harrier.
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] Duct heating was used by Pratt & Whitney for their JTF17 turbofan proposal for the U.S.
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] Supersonic Transport Program in 1964 and a demonstrator engine was run.
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] The duct heater used an annular combustor and would be used for takeoff, climb and cruise at Mach 2.7 with different amounts of augmentation depending on aircraft weight.
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] A jet engine afterburner is an extended exhaust section containing extra fuel injectors.
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] Since the jet engine upstream (i.e., before the turbine) will use little of the oxygen it ingests, additional fuel can be burned after the gas flow has left the turbines.
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] When the afterburner is turned on, fuel is injected and igniters are fired.
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] The resulting combustion process increases the afterburner exit (nozzle entry) temperature, resulting in a significant increase in engine thrust.
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] The resulting increase in afterburner exit volume flow is accommodated by increasing the throat area of the exit nozzle.
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] Otherwise, if pressure is not released, the gas can flow upstream and re-ignite, possibly causing a compressor stall (or fan surge in a turbofan application).
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] Solar afterburners used on the F7U Cutlass, F-94 Starfire and F-89 Scorpion, had 2-position eyelid nozzles.
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] Modern designs incorporate not only variable-geometry (VG) nozzles but multiple stages of augmentation via separate spray bars.
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] To a first order, the gross thrust ratio (afterburning/dry) is directly proportional to the root of the stagnation temperature ratio across the afterburner (i.e. exit/entry).
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] Due to their high fuel consumption, afterburners are only used for short-duration, high-thrust requirements.
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] These include heavy-weight or short-runway take-offs, assisting catapult launches from aircraft carriers, and during air combat.
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] A notable exception is the Pratt & Whitney J58 engine used in the SR-71 Blackbird which used its afterburner for prolonged periods and was refueled in-flight as part of every reconnaissance mission.
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] An afterburner has a limited life to match its intermittent use.
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] The J58 was an exception with a continuous rating.
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] This was achieved with thermal barrier coatings on the liner and flame holders and by cooling the liner and nozzle with compressor bleed air instead of turbine exhaust gas.
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] In heat engines such as jet engines, efficiency is highest when combustion occurs at the highest pressure and temperature possible, and expanded down to ambient pressure (see Carnot cycle).
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] Since the exhaust gas already has a reduced oxygen content, owing to previous combustion, and since the fuel is not burning in a highly compressed air column, the afterburner is generally inefficient in comparison to the main combustion process.
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] Afterburner efficiency also declines significantly if, as is usually the case, the inlet and tailpipe pressure decreases with increasing altitude.
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] This limitation applies only to turbojets.
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] In a military turbofan combat engine, the bypass air is added into the exhaust, thereby increasing the core and afterburner efficiency.
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] In turbojets the gain is limited to 50%, whereas in a turbofan it depends on the bypass ratio and can be as much as 70%.
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] However, as a counterexample, the SR-71 had reasonable efficiency at high altitude in afterburning ("wet") mode owing to its high speed (Mach 3.2) and correspondingly high pressure due to ram intake.
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] Afterburning has a significant influence upon engine cycle choice.
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] Lowering the fan pressure ratio decreases specific thrust (both dry and wet afterburning), but results in a lower temperature entering the afterburner.
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] Since the afterburning exit temperature is effectively fixed, the temperature rise across the unit increases, raising the afterburner fuel flow.
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] The total fuel flow tends to increase faster than the net thrust, resulting in a higher specific fuel consumption (SFC).
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] However, the corresponding dry power SFC improves (i.e. lower specific thrust).
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] The high temperature ratio across the afterburner results in a good thrust boost.
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] If the aircraft burns a large percentage of its fuel with the afterburner alight, it pays to select an engine cycle with a high specific thrust (i.e. high fan pressure ratio/low bypass ratio).
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] The resulting engine is relatively fuel efficient with afterburning (i.e.
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] Combat/Take-off), but thirsty in dry power.
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] If, however, the afterburner is to be hardly used, a low specific thrust (low fan pressure ratio/high bypass ratio) cycle will be favored.
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] Such an engine has a good dry SFC, but a poor afterburning SFC at Combat/Take-off.
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] Often the engine designer is faced with a compromise between these two extremes.
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] The Caproni Campini C.C.2 motorjet, designed by the Italian engineer Secondo Campini, was the first aircraft to incorporate an afterburner.
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] The first flight of a C.C.2, with its afterburners operating, took place on 11 April 1941.
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] Early British afterburner ("reheat") work included flight tests on a Rolls-Royce W2/B23 in a Gloster Meteor I in late 1944 and ground tests on a Power Jets W2/700 engine in mid-1945.
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] This engine was destined for the Miles M.52 supersonic aircraft project.
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] Early American research on the concept was done by NACA, in Cleveland, Ohio, leading to the publication of the paper "Theoretical Investigation of Thrust Augmentation of Turbojet Engines by Tail-pipe Burning" in January 1947.
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] American work on afterburners in 1948 resulted in installations on early straight-wing jets such as the Pirate, Starfire and Scorpion.
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] The new Pratt & Whitney J48 turbojet, at 8,000 lbf (36 kN) thrust with afterburners, would power the Grumman swept-wing fighter F9F-6, which was about to go into production.
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] Other new Navy fighters with afterburners included the Chance Vought F7U-3 Cutlass, powered by two 6,000 lbf (27 kN) thrust Westinghouse J46 engines.
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] In the 1950s, several large afterburning engines were developed, such as the Orenda Iroquois and the British de Havilland Gyron and Rolls-Royce Avon RB.146 variants.
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] The Avon and its variants powered the English Electric Lightning, the first supersonic aircraft in RAF service.
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] The Bristol-Siddeley/Rolls-Royce Olympus was fitted with afterburners for use with the BAC TSR-2.
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] This system was designed and developed jointly by Bristol-Siddeley and Solar of San Diego.
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] The afterburner system for the Concorde was developed by Snecma.
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] Afterburners are generally used only in military aircraft, and are considered standard equipment on fighter aircraft.
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] The handful of civilian planes that have used them include some NASA research aircraft, the Tupolev Tu-144, Concorde and the White Knight of Scaled Composites.
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] Concorde flew long distances at supersonic speeds.
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] Sustained high speeds would be impossible with the high fuel consumption of afterburner, and the plane used afterburners at takeoff and to minimize time spent in the high-drag transonic flight regime.
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] Supersonic flight without afterburners is referred to as supercruise.
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] A turbojet engine equipped with an afterburner is called an "afterburning turbojet", whereas a turbofan engine similarly equipped is sometimes called an "augmented turbofan".
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] A "dump-and-burn" is an airshow display feature where fuel is jettisoned, then intentionally ignited using the afterburner.
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] A spectacular flame combined with high speed makes this a popular display for airshows, or as a finale to fireworks.
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] Fuel dumping is used primarily to reduce the weight of an aircraft to avoid a heavy, high-speed landing.
[src:jet-engine-performance/afterburner] Other than for safety or emergency reasons, fuel dumping does not have a practical use.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] The aircraft was carrying 74 passengers and five crew members.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] Only four passengers and one crew member (flight attendant Kelly Duncan) were rescued from the crash and survived.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] Williams Jr., assisted in the rescue of the survivors, but drowned before he could be rescued.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] Four motorists on the bridge were killed.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] The survivors were rescued from the icy river by civilians and professionals.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] President Ronald Reagan commended these acts during his State of the Union speech 13 days later.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] The National Transportation Safety Board (NTSB) determined that the cause of the accident was pilot error.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] The aircraft involved, a 13-year-old Boeing 737-222, registered as N62AF, was manufactured in 1969 and previously flown by United Airlines under the registration N9050U.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] The aircraft was powered by two Pratt & Whitney JT8D-9A turbofan engines, and had flown over 27,000 hours before the accident.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] Wheaton, aged 34, was hired by Air Florida in October 1978 as a first officer.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] He was promoted to captain in August 1980.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] At the time of the accident, he had about 8,300 total flight hours, with 2,322 hours of commercial jet experience, all logged at Air Florida.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] He had logged 1,752 hours on the Boeing 737, the accident aircraft type, 1,100 of those hours as captain.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] Wheaton was described by fellow pilots as a quiet person, with good operational skills and knowledge, who had operated well in high-workload flying situations.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] His leadership style was described as similar to those of other pilots.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] On May 8, 1980, though, he was suspended after failing a Boeing 737 company line check and was found to be unsatisfactory in these areas: adherence to regulations, checklist usage, flight procedures such as departures and autopilot usage, and approaches and landings.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] He resumed his duties after passing a retest on August 27, 1980.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] On April 24, 1981, he received an unsatisfactory grade on a company recurrent proficiency check when he showed deficiencies in memory items, knowledge of aircraft systems, and aircraft limitations.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] Three days later, he satisfactorily passed a proficiency recheck.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] Pettit, aged 31, was hired by Air Florida on October 3, 1980, as a first officer on the Boeing 737.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] At the time of the accident, he had around 3,353 flight hours, 992 with Air Florida, all on the 737.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] From October 1977 to October 1980, he had been a fighter pilot in the US Air Force, accumulating 669 hours as a flight examiner, instructor pilot, and ground instructor in an F-15 fighter unit.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] The first officer was described by personal friends and pilots as a witty, bright, outgoing individual with an excellent command of physical and mental skills in aircraft piloting.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] Pilots normally alternate who flies each leg.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] One pilot is designated the pilot flying (PF) and the other the pilot monitoring (PM); however, the Captain retains ultimate authority for all aircraft operations.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] The first officer was the Pilot flying during this accident.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] The three cabin crew consisted of Senior Flight Attendant Donna Adams (23) with 4 years' service at Air Florida, Marilyn Nichols (25) with 3 years' service, and Kelly Duncan (23) with 3 years' service.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] On Wednesday, January 13, 1982, Washington National Airport (DCA) was closed following a heavy snowstorm, which produced 6.5 inches (17 cm) of snow.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] It reopened at noon under marginal conditions as the snowfall decreased.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] That afternoon, the plane was to return to Fort Lauderdale–Hollywood International Airport, with an intermediate stop at Tampa International Airport.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] The scheduled departure time was delayed about 1 hour and 45 minutes because of a backlog of arrivals and departures caused by the temporary closing of Washington National Airport.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] As the plane was readied for departure, moderate snowfall continued with a temperature of 24 °F (−4 °C).
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] The Boeing 737 was de-iced with a mixture of heated water and monopropylene glycol by American Airlines, under a ground-service agreement with Air Florida.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] That agreement specified that covers for the pitot tubes, static ports, and engine inlets had to be used, but the American Airlines employees failed to comply with those rules.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] One deicing vehicle was used by two different operators, who chose widely different mixture percentages to de-ice the left and right sides of the aircraft.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] Subsequent testing of the deicing truck showed, "the mixture dispensed differed substantially from the mixture selected" (18% actual vs.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] The plane had trouble leaving the gate when the ground-services tug could not get traction on the icy ramp.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] For roughly 30 to 90 seconds, the crew attempted to back away from the gate using the reverse thrust of the engines (a powerback), which proved futile.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] Boeing operations bulletins had warned against using reverse thrust in those kinds of conditions.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] Eventually, a ground tug unit properly equipped with snow chains was used to push the aircraft back from the gate.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] After leaving the gate, the aircraft waited in a taxi line with many other aircraft for 49 minutes before reaching the takeoff runway.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] The pilot apparently decided not to return to the gate for reapplication of deicing, fearing that the flight's departure would be even further delayed.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] More snow and ice accumulated on the wings during that period, and the crew was aware of that fact when they decided to take off.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] Heavy snow was falling during their takeoff roll at 3:59 pm EST.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] Though the outside temperature was well below freezing and snow was falling, the crew did not activate the engine anti-ice systems.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] This system uses heat from the engines to prevent sensors and the engine intake cowl from accumulating ice or snow, ensuring accurate readings.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] As a result, this caused the engine pressure ratio (EPR) thrust indicators to provide false readings.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] The correct engine power setting for the temperature and airport altitude of Washington National at the time was 2.04 EPR, but analysis of the engine noise recorded on the cockpit voice recorder indicated that the actual power output corresponded with an engine pressure ratio of only 1.70.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] Neither pilot had much experience flying in snowy, cold weather.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] The captain had made only eight takeoffs or landings in snowy conditions on the 737, and the first officer had flown in snow only twice.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] Adding to the plane's troubles was the pilots' decision to maneuver closely behind a DC-9 that was taxiing just ahead of them prior to takeoff, due to their mistaken belief that the warmth from the DC-9's engines would melt the snow and ice that had accumulated on Flight 90's wings.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] This action, which went specifically against flight-manual recommendations for an icing situation, actually contributed to icing on the 737.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] The exhaust gases from the other aircraft melted the snow on the wings, but instead of falling off the plane during takeoff, this slush mixture froze on the wings' leading edges and the engine inlet nose cone.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] The captain dismissed these concerns and let the takeoff proceed.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] Investigators determined that plenty of time and space on the runway remained for the captain to have abandoned the takeoff, and criticized his refusal to listen to his first officer, who was correct that the instrument panel readings were wrong.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] The pilot was told not to delay because another aircraft was 2.5 nautical miles (2.9 mi; 4.6 km) out on final approach to the same runway.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] The following is a transcript of Flight 90's cockpit voice recorder during the plane's acceleration down the runway.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] The aircraft traveled almost half a mile (800 m) farther down the runway than is customary before liftoff was accomplished.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] Survivors of the crash indicated the trip over the runway was extremely rough, with survivor Joe Stiley—a businessman and private pilot—saying that he believed that they would not get airborne and would "fall off the end of the runway".
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] When the plane became airborne, Stiley told his co-worker (and survivor) Nikki Felch to assume the crash position, with some nearby passengers following their example.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] Although the 737 did manage to become airborne, it attained a maximum altitude of just 352 feet (107 m) before it began losing altitude.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] Recorders later indicated that the aircraft was airborne for just 30 seconds.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] At 4:01 pm EST, it crashed into the 14th Street Bridge across the Potomac River, 0.75 nmi (0.9 mi; 1.4 km) from the end of the runway.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] The plane hit six cars and a truck on the bridge, and tore away 97 feet (30 m) of the bridge's rail and 41 feet (12 m) of the bridge's wall.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] The aircraft then plunged into the freezing Potomac River.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] It fell between two of the three spans of the bridge, between the I-395 northbound span (the Rochambeau Bridge) and the high-occupancy vehicle lane north- and southbound spans, about 200 ft (70 yd; 60 m) offshore.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] All but the tail section quickly became submerged.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] Clinging to the tail section of the broken airliner in the ice-choked Potomac River were flight attendant Kelly Duncan and four passengers: Patricia "Nikki" Felch, Joe Stiley, Arland D.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] (strapped and tangled in his seat), and Priscilla Tirado.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] Duncan inflated the only flotation device they could find, and passed it to the severely injured Felch.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] Passenger Bert Hamilton, who was floating in the water nearby, was the first to be pulled from the water.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] Many federal offices in downtown Washington had closed early that day in response to quickly developing blizzard conditions.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] Thus, significant backups of traffic existed on almost all of the city's roads, which made it unusually difficult for ambulances to reach the crash site.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] The Coast Guard's 65-foot (20 m) harbor tugboat *Capstan* (WYTL 65601) and its crew were based nearby; their duties include icebreaking and responding to water rescues.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] The *Capstan* was considerably farther downriver on another search-and-rescue mission.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] Emergency ground response was hampered by ice-covered roads and gridlocked traffic; ambulances dispatched at 4:07 pm took 20 minutes to reach the crash scene.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] Ambulances attempting to reach the crash site were even driven down the sidewalk in front of the White House.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] Rescuers who reached the site were unable to assist survivors in the water because they did not have adequate equipment to reach them.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] Water temperature, about 34 °F (1 °C), and heavy ice made swimming out to the victims impossible.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] Multiple attempts to throw a makeshift lifeline (made of belts and other items which could be tied together) out to the survivors proved ineffective.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] The rescue attempts by emergency officials and witnesses were recorded and broadcast live by area news reporters, and because the accident occurred in the nation's capital, large numbers of media personnel were on hand to provide quick and extensive coverage.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] Roger Olian, a sheet-metal foreman at St.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] Elizabeths Hospital, a Washington psychiatric hospital, was on his way home across the 14th Street Bridge when he heard a man yelling that an aircraft was in the water.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] He was the first to jump into the water to attempt to reach the survivors.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] At the same time, several military personnel from the Pentagon—Steve Raynes, Aldo De La Cruz, and Steve Bell—ran to the water's edge to help Olian.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] At this point, air traffic controllers and flight controllers were aware only that the plane had disappeared from radar and was not responding to radio calls, and had no idea what had happened or where the plane was located.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] Around 4:20 pm EST, *Eagle 1*, a United States Park Police Bell 206L-1 Long Ranger helicopter, based at the "Eagles Nest" at Anacostia Park in Washington, arrived and began attempting to airlift the survivors to shore.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] At great risk to themselves, the crew worked close to the water's surface, at one time coming so close to the ice-clogged river that the helicopter's skids dipped beneath the surface.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] At this point, survivors had been in the 34-degree water for over 20 minutes.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] The helicopter crew lowered a line to survivors to tow them to shore.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] First to receive the line was Bert Hamilton, who was treading water about 10 feet (3 m) from the plane's floating tail and closest to the helicopter.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] The pilot pulled him across the ice to shore, while avoiding the sides of the bridge.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] By then, some fire and rescue personnel had arrived to join the military personnel and civilians who pulled Hamilton (and the next, last three survivors) from the water's edge up to waiting ambulances; rescuers and civilians on the banks had to duck to avoid the helicopter's rotors.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] The helicopter returned to the aircraft's tail, and this time Arland D.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] (sometimes referred to as "the sixth passenger") caught the line.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] Williams, not able to unstrap himself from the wreckage, passed the line to flight attendant Kelly Duncan, who was airlifted to shore.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] On its third trip back to the wreckage, the helicopter lowered two lifelines, fearing that the remaining survivors had only a few minutes before succumbing to hypothermia.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] Williams, still strapped into the wreckage, passed one line to Joe Stiley, who was holding on to panic-stricken Priscilla Tirado, who had lost her husband and baby.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] Stiley's co-worker, Nikki Felch, took the second line.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] As the helicopter pulled the three through the water and blocks of ice toward shore, both Tirado and Felch lost their grip and fell back into the water.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] While being dragged through the ice to the riverbank by the helicopter, Stiley broke multiple ribs.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] Tirado, seriously injured and blinded by jet fuel, was too weak to grab the line when the helicopter returned to her.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] A watching bystander, Congressional Budget Office assistant Lenny Skutnik, stripped off his coat and boots, and in short sleeves, dove into the icy water and swam out to successfully pull her to shore.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] The helicopter then proceeded to where Felch had fallen, and paramedic Gene Windsor stepped onto the helicopter skid and grabbed Felch's clothing to lift her onto the skid and bring her to shore.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] Ten minutes passed from the time the helicopter arrived on scene until Felch's rescue.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] When the helicopter crew returned for Williams, the wreckage he was strapped into had rolled slightly, submerging him; according to the coroner, Williams was the only passenger to die by drowning.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] His body and those of the other occupants were recovered later.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] The inclement weather had caused an early start to Washington's rush-hour traffic, frustrating the response time of emergency crews.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] The early rush hour also meant that trains on the Washington Metro were full when, just 30 minutes after Flight 90 crashed, the Metro suffered its first fatal crash at Federal Triangle station.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] This meant that Washington's nearest airport, one of its main bridges in or out of the city, and one of its busiest subway lines were all closed simultaneously, paralyzing much of the metropolitan area.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] The first member of the news media to arrive was Chester Panzer of WRC-TV.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] Panzer and a crew member were stuck in traffic in their news vehicle on the George Washington Parkway when the plane crashed a few hundred yards from them.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] Minutes later, they were shooting video footage of the crash scene, depicting wreckage and survivors in the water, along with the arrival of first responders.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] Panzer captured Skutnik's dive to pull Tirado from the water.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] Panzer was a 1983 Pulitzer Prize finalist for this spot news photography.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] Charles "Charlie" Pereira, a photographer with the United States Park Police, immediately ran to the 14th Street Bridge upon learning of the crash and captured the only still images from the rescue.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] He was nominated for a Pulitzer Prize for his photography.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] John Goldsmith, an off-beat reporter for WDVM-TV (now WUSA), was coincidentally at National Airport prior to the incident reporting on the snowstorm, and even caught footage of Flight 90 prior to takeoff.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] Among the plethora of news coverage of the incident, *The Washington Post* published a story about the then-unidentified survivor of the crash, Arland D.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] The day after the crash, WWDC "shock jock" Howard Stern pretended to call the Air Florida ticket counter to ask about buying tickets to the 14th Street Bridge.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] The 737 had broken into several large pieces upon impact—the nose and cockpit section, the cabin up to the wing attachment point, the cabin from behind the wings to the rear airstairs, and the empennage.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] Although actual impact speeds were low and well within survivability limits, the structural breakup of the fuselage and exposure to freezing water nonetheless proved fatal for all persons aboard the plane except those seated in the tail section.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] The NTSB concluded that the accident was not survivable.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] Determining the position of the rudder, slats, elevators, and ailerons was not possible due to impact damage and destruction of the majority of flight control systems.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] The NTSB determined that the probable cause of the crash included the flight crew's failure to enforce a sterile cockpit during the final preflight checklist procedure.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] The engines' anti-ice heaters were not engaged during ground operation and takeoff.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] The decision to take off with snow/ice on the airfoil surfaces of the aircraft, and the captain's failure to reject the takeoff during the early stage, when his attention was called to anomalous engine instrument readings, were also erroneous.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] The "sixth passenger", who had survived the crash and had repeatedly given up the rescue lines to other survivors before drowning, was later identified as 46-year-old bank examiner Arland D.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] The repaired span of the 14th Street Bridge complex over the Potomac River at the crash site, then named the Rochambeau Bridge, was renamed the Arland D.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] The Citadel in South Carolina, from which he graduated in 1957, has several memorials to him.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] Elementary School was dedicated in his hometown of Mattoon in Coles County, Illinois.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] Civilians Roger Olian and Lenny Skutnik received the Coast Guard's Gold Lifesaving Medal.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] Williams, Jr. also received the award posthumously.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] Skutnik was introduced to the joint session of the U.S.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] Congress during President Ronald Reagan's State of the Union speech later that month.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] The Coast Guard awarded a Silver Lifesaving Medal to two crewmen of the U.S.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] Park Police are part of the United States Department of the Interior, pilot Donald W.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] Windsor also received the Interior Department's Valor Award, presented in a special ceremony soon after the accident by Secretary of the Interior James G.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] Usher later became superintendent of the National Park Service Law Enforcement Training Center located at FLETC in Brunswick, Georgia, before retiring in December 2012.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] Roger Olian, Lenny Skutnik, Donald Usher, and Melvin Windsor each received the Carnegie Hero Fund Medal.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] Kelly Duncan, the only surviving flight attendant, was recognized in the NTSB accident report for her "unselfish act" of giving the only life vest she could find to a passenger.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] The investigation following the crash, especially regarding the failure of the captain to respond to crew concerns about the deicing procedure, led to a number of reforms in pilot-training regulations.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] Partial blame was placed on the young, inexperienced flight crew, who had a combined age of only 65 and had begun their careers as commercial pilots less than five years earlier.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] Typical of upstart, low-cost carriers, Air Florida frequently hired youthful pilots who worked for less money than veterans, and were for the most part seeking to gain flight experience prior to joining a major airline.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] It became a widely used case study for both air crews and rescue workers.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] The Discovery Channel Canada/National Geographic TV series *Mayday* (also called *Air Crash Investigation* or *Air Emergency*) dramatized the accident in an episode titled "Disaster on the Potomac" (aired in some countries as "Tragedy on the Potomac").
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] The crash was featured in season 2, episode 2, of the TV show *Why Planes Crash*, in an episode called "Brush with Death".
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] The National Geographic Channel series *Seconds from Disaster* also dramatized the accident entitled "Plane Crash in the Potomac".
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] The crash was also dramatized in the 1984 made-for-TV movie *Flight 90: Disaster on the Potomac*.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] The flight has also been shown on the show *When Weather Changed History* on American-based The Weather Channel.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] The National Law Enforcement Museum, which opened in Washington, D.C. in 2018, has footage of the crash on display along with interviews of survivors and other first-hand accounts.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] Park Police helicopter involved in the rescue of Flight 90's survivors.
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] Arland D Williams, Jr., is commemorated in Sara Hickman's song "Last Man in the Water".
[src:jet-engine-performance/air-florida-flight-90] Air Florida Flight 90 is described in Season 2, Episode 1 of the HBO series, *The Rehearsal*.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The **Airbus A380** is a large wide-body airliner, developed and produced by Airbus from 2003 to 2021.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] It is the world's largest passenger airliner and the only full-length double-deck jet airliner.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Airbus studies started in 1988, and the project was announced in 1990 to challenge the dominance of the Boeing 747 in the long-haul market.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The then-designated A3XX project was presented in 1994 and Airbus launched the €9.5 billion (US$10.7 billion) A380 programme on 19 December 2000.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The first prototype was unveiled in Toulouse, France on 18 January 2005, commencing its first flight on 27 April 2005.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] It then obtained its type certificate from the European Aviation Safety Agency (EASA) and the US Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) on 12 December 2006.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Due to difficulties with the electrical wiring, the initial production was delayed by two years and the development costs almost doubled.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] It was first delivered to Singapore Airlines on 15 October 2007 and entered service on 25 October.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Production peaked at 30 per year in both 2012 and 2014, with manufacturing of the aircraft ending in 2021.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The A380's estimated $25 billion development cost was not recouped by the time Airbus ended production.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The full-length double-deck aircraft has a typical seating for 525 passengers, with a maximum certified capacity for 853 passengers.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The quadjet is powered by Engine Alliance GP7200 or Rolls-Royce Trent 900 turbofans providing a range of 8,000 nmi (14,800 km; 9,200 mi).
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] As of December 2021, the global A380 fleet had completed more than 800,000 flights over 7.3 million block hours with no fatalities and no hull losses.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] As of April 2024, there were 189 aircraft in service with 10 operators worldwide.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Of its fifteen total operating airlines, five have fully retired the A380 from their fleets.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] In mid-1988, Airbus engineers, led by Jean Roeder, began work in secret on the development of an ultra-high-capacity airliner (UHCA), both to complete its own range of products and to break the dominance that Boeing had enjoyed in this market segment since the early 1970s with its Boeing 747.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] McDonnell Douglas unsuccessfully offered its double-deck MD-12 concept for sale.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Lockheed was exploring the possibility for a Very Large Subsonic Transport.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Roeder was given approval for further evaluations of the UHCA after a formal presentation to the President and CEO in June 1990.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The megaproject was announced at the 1990 Farnborough Airshow, with the stated goal of 15% lower operating costs than the Boeing 747-400.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Airbus organised four teams of designers, one from each of its partners (Aérospatiale, British Aerospace, Deutsche Aerospace AG, CASA) to propose new technologies for its future aircraft designs.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The designs were presented in 1992 and the most competitive designs were used.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] In January 1993, Boeing and several companies in the Airbus consortium started a joint feasibility study of a Very Large Commercial Transport (VLCT), aiming to form a partnership to share the limited market.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] In June 1994, Airbus announced its plan to develop its own very large airliner, designated as A3XX.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Airbus considered several designs, including an unusual side-by-side combination of two fuselages from its A340, the largest Airbus jet at the time.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The A3XX was pitted against the VLCT study and Boeing's own New Large Aircraft successor to the 747.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] In July 1995, the joint study with Boeing was abandoned, as Boeing's interest had declined due to analysis that such a product was unlikely to cover the projected $15 billion development cost.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Despite the fact that only two airlines had expressed public interest in purchasing such a plane, Airbus was already pursuing its own large-plane project.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Analysts suggested that Boeing would instead pursue stretching its 747 design, and that air travel was already moving away from the hub-and-spoke system that consolidated traffic into large planes, and toward more non-stop routes that could be served by smaller planes.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] From 1997 to 2000, as the 1997 Asian financial crisis darkened the market outlook, Airbus refined its design, targeting a 15–20% reduction in operating costs over the existing Boeing 747-400.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The A3XX design converged on a double-decker layout that provided more passenger volume than a traditional single-deck design.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Airbus did so in line with traditional hub-and-spoke theory, as opposed to the point-to-point theory with the Boeing 777, after conducting an extensive market analysis with over 200 focus groups.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Although early marketing of the huge cross-section touted the possibility of duty-free shops, restaurant-like dining, gyms, casinos and beauty parlours on board, the realities of airline economics have kept such dreams grounded.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] On 19 December 2000, the supervisory board of newly restructured Airbus voted to launch a €9.5 billion ($10.7 billion) project to build the A3XX, re-designated as A380, with 50 firm orders from six launch customers.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The A380 designation was a break from previous Airbus families, which had progressed sequentially from A300 to A340.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] It was chosen because the number 8 resembles the double-deck cross section, and is a lucky number in many East Asian countries where the aircraft was being marketed.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The aircraft configuration was finalised in early 2001, and manufacturing of the first A380 wing-box component started on 23 January 2002.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The development cost of the A380 had grown to €11–14 billion when the first aircraft was completed.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] In 2000, the projected development cost was €9.5 billion.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] In 2004, Airbus estimated that €1.5 billion (US$2 billion) would need to be added, totalling the developmental costs to €10.3 billion ($12.7 billion).
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] In 2006, Airbus stopped publishing its reported cost after reaching costs of €10.2 billion and then it provisioned another €4.9 billion, after the difficulties in electric cabling and two years delay for an estimated total of €18 billion.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] In 2014, the aircraft was estimated to have cost $25bn (£16bn, €18.9bn) to develop.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] In 2015, Airbus said development costs were €15 billion (£11.4 billion, $16.64 billion), though analysts believe the figure is likely to be at least €5bn ($5.55 Bn) more for a €20 Bn ($22.19 Bn) total.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] In 2016, The A380 development costs were estimated at $25 billion for 15 years, $25–30 billion, or €25 billion ($28 billion).
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] To start the programme in 2000, the governments of France, Germany and the UK loaned Airbus €3.5 billion and refundable advances reached €5.9 billion ($7.3 billion).
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] In February 2018, after an Emirates order secured production of the unprofitable programme for ten years, Airbus revised its deal with the three loan-giving governments to save $1.4 billion (17%) and restructured terms to lower the production rate from eight per year in 2019 to six per year.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] In February 2019, the German government disclosed that it was conducting talks with Airbus regarding €600 million in outstanding loans.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Following the decision to wind down the A380 programme, Europe argues that the subsidies in effect no longer exist and that no sanctions are warranted.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Major structural sections of the A380 were built in France, Germany, Spain, and the United Kingdom.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Due to the sections' large size, traditional transportation methods proved unfeasible, so they were taken to the *Jean-Luc Lagardère Plant* assembly hall in Toulouse, France, by specialised road and water transportation, though some parts were moved by the A300-600ST *Beluga* transport aircraft.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] A380 components were provided by suppliers from around the world; the four largest contributors, by value, were Rolls-Royce, Safran, United Technologies and General Electric.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] For the surface movement of large A380 structural components, a complex route known as the Itinéraire à Grand Gabarit was developed.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] This involved the construction of a fleet of roll-on/roll-off (RORO) ships and barges, the construction of port facilities and the development of new and modified roads to accommodate oversized road convoys.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The front and rear fuselage sections were shipped on one of three RORO ships from Hamburg in northern Germany to Saint-Nazaire in France.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The ship travelled via the UK, where the wings were manufactured at Broughton, north Wales, and were then transported by barge to the nearby docks of Mostyn, where they were loaded for ship transport.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] In Saint-Nazaire, the ship exchanged the fuselage sections from Hamburg for larger, assembled sections, some of which included the nose.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] It then went to pick up the belly and tail sections from Construcciones Aeronáuticas SA in Cádiz, Spain, and delivered them to Bordeaux.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] From there, the A380 parts were transported by barge to Langon, and by oversize road convoys to the assembly hall in Toulouse.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] To avoid damage from direct handling, parts were secured in custom jigs carried on self-powered wheeled vehicles.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] After assembly, the aircraft were flown to the Airbus Hamburg-Finkenwerder plant to be furnished and painted.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Airbus sized the production facilities and supply chain for a production rate of four A380s per month.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] In 2005, five A380s were built for testing and demonstration purposes.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The first A380, registered F-WWOW, was unveiled in Toulouse 18 January 2005.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] This plane, equipped with Rolls-Royce Trent 900 engines, flew from Toulouse–Blagnac Airport with a crew of six headed by chief test pilot Jacques Rosay.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Rosay said flying the A380 had been "like handling a bicycle".
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] On 1 December 2005, the A380 achieved its maximum design speed of Mach 0.96, (its design cruise speed is Mach 0.85) in a shallow dive.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] In 2006, the A380 flew its first high-altitude test at Addis Ababa Bole International Airport.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] It conducted its second high-altitude test at the same airport in 2009.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] On 10 January 2006, it flew to José María Córdova International Airport in Colombia, accomplishing the transatlantic testing, and then it went to El Dorado International Airport to test the engine operation in high-altitude airports.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] It arrived in North America on 6 February 2006, landing in Iqaluit, Nunavut, in Canada for cold-weather testing.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] On 14 February 2006, during the destructive wing strength certification test on MSN5000, the test wing of the A380 failed at 145% of the limit load, short of the required 150% level.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Airbus announced modifications adding 30 kg (66 lb) to the wing to provide the required strength.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] On 26 March 2006, the A380 underwent evacuation certification in Hamburg.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] With 8 of the 16 exits randomly blocked, 853 mixed passengers and 20 crew exited the darkened aircraft in 78 seconds, less than the 90 seconds required for certification.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Three days later, the A380 received European Aviation Safety Agency (EASA) and United States Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) approval to carry up to 853 passengers.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The first A380 using GP7200 engines – serial number MSN009 and flew on 25 August 2006.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] On 4 September 2006, the first full passenger-carrying flight test took place.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The aircraft flew from Toulouse with 474 Airbus employees on board, in a test of passenger facilities and comfort.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] In November 2006, a further series of route-proving flights demonstrated the aircraft's performance for 150 flight hours under typical airline operating conditions.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] As of 2014, the A380 test aircraft continue to perform test procedures.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Airbus obtained type certificates for the A380-841 and A380-842 model from the EASA and FAA on 12 December 2006 in a joint ceremony at the company's French headquarters, receiving the ICAO code A388.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The A380-861 model was added to the type certificate on 14 December 2007.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Initial production of the A380 was troubled by delays attributed to the 530 km (330 mi) of wiring in each aircraft.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Airbus cited as underlying causes the complexity of the cabin wiring (98,000 wires and 40,000 connectors), its concurrent design and production, the high degree of customisation for each airline, and failures of configuration management and change control.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The German and Spanish Airbus facilities continued to use CATIA version 4, while British and French sites migrated to version 5.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] File conversion tools were initially developed by Airbus to help solve this problem; however, the digital mock-up was still unable to read the full technical design data.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Furthermore, organisational culture was also cited as a cause of the production delays.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The communication and reporting culture at the time frowned upon delivery of bad news, meaning Airbus was unable to take early actions to mitigate technical and production issues.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Airbus announced the first delay in June 2005 and notified airlines that deliveries would be delayed by six months.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] This reduced the total number of planned deliveries by the end of 2009 from about 120 to 90–100.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] On 13 June 2006, Airbus announced a second delay, with the delivery schedule slipping an additional six to seven months.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Although the first delivery was still planned before the end of 2006, deliveries in 2007 would drop to only 9 aircraft, and deliveries by the end of 2009 would be cut to 70–80 aircraft.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The announcement caused a 26% drop in the share price of Airbus' parent, EADS, and led to the departure of EADS CEO Paul Dupont, Airbus CEO Gustav Humbert, and A380 programme manager Charles Champion.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] On 3 October 2006, upon completion of a review of the A380 programme, Airbus CEO Christian Streiff announced a third delay, pushing the first delivery to October 2007, to be followed by 13 deliveries in 2008, 25 in 2009, and the full production rate of 45 aircraft per year in 2010.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The delay also increased the earnings shortfall projected by Airbus through 2010 to €4.8 billion.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] As Airbus prioritised the work on the A380-800 over the A380F, freighter orders were cancelled by FedEx and United Parcel Service, or converted to A380-800 by Emirates and ILFC.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Airbus suspended work on the freighter version, but said it remained on offer, albeit without a service entry date.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] For the passenger version Airbus negotiated a revised delivery schedule and compensation with the 13 customers, all of which retained their orders with some placing subsequent orders, including Emirates, Singapore Airlines, Qantas, Air France, Qatar Airways, and Korean Air.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] On 13 May 2008, Airbus announced reduced deliveries for the years 2008 (12) and 2009 (21).
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] After further manufacturing setbacks, Airbus announced its plan to deliver 14 A380s in 2009, down from the previously revised target of 18.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] A total of 10 A380s were delivered in 2009.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] In 2010, Airbus delivered 18 of the expected 20 A380s, due to Rolls-Royce engine availability problems.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Airbus planned to deliver "between 20 and 25" A380s in 2011 before ramping up to three a month in 2012.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] In fact, Airbus delivered 26 units, thus outdoing its predicted output for the first time.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] As of July 2012, production was 3 aircraft per month.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Among the production problems are challenging interiors, interiors being installed sequentially rather than concurrently as in smaller planes, and union and government objections to streamlining to improve manufacturing productivity.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Nicknamed The "*Superjumbo"*, the first A380, MSN003, was delivered to Singapore Airlines on 15 October 2007 and entered service on 25 October 2007 with flight number SQ380 between Singapore and Sydney.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Passengers bought seats in a charity online auction paying between $560 and $100,380.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Two months later, Singapore Airlines CEO Chew Choong Seng stated the A380 was performing better than either the airline or Airbus had anticipated, burning 20% less fuel per seat-mile than the airline's 747-400 fleet.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Emirates' Tim Clark claimed that the A380 has better fuel economy at Mach 0.86 than at 0.83, and that its technical dispatch reliability is at 97%, the same as Singapore Airlines.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Airbus is committed to reach the industry standard of 98.5%.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Emirates was the second airline to receive the A380 and commenced service between Dubai and New York in August 2008.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Qantas followed, with flights between Melbourne and Los Angeles in October 2008.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] By the end of 2008, 890,000 passengers had flown on 2,200 flights.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] In February 2008, the A380 became the first airliner to fly using synthetic liquid fuel.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The fuel is processed from gas to liquid form (GTL fuel).
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The flight was 3 hours long, taking off from Filton, UK, and landing in Toulouse, France, and was a significant step in evaluating the suitability of sustainable aviation fuels.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] In 2010, Airbus announced a new A380 build standard, incorporating a strengthened airframe structure and a 1.5° increase in wing twist.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Airbus also offered, as an option, an improved maximum take-off weight, thus providing a better payload/range performance.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Maximum take-off weight was increased by 4 t (8,800 lb), to 573 t (1,263,000 lb) and the range was extended by 100 nautical miles (190 km; 120 mi); this was achieved by reducing flight loads, partly from optimising the fly-by-wire control laws.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] British Airways and Emirates were the first two customers to have received this new option in 2013.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Emirates asked for an update with new engines for the A380 to be competitive with the Boeing 777X around 2020, and Airbus was studying 11-abreast seating.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] In 2012, Airbus announced another increase in the A380's maximum take-off weight to 575 t (1,268,000 lb), a 6 t increase from the initial A380 variant and 2 t higher than the increased-weight proposal of 2010.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] This increased the range by some 150 nautical miles (280 km; 170 mi), taking its capability to around 8,350 nautical miles (15,460 km; 9,610 mi) at current payloads.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The higher-weight version was offered for introduction to service early in 2013.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] During repairs following the Qantas Flight 32 engine failure incident, cracks were discovered in wing fittings.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] As a result, the European Aviation Safety Agency issued an Airworthiness Directive in January 2012 which affected 20 A380 aircraft that had accumulated over 1,300 flights.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] A380s with under 1,800 flight hours were to be inspected within 6 weeks or 84 flights; aircraft with over 1,800 flight hours were to be examined within four days or 14 flights.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Fittings found to be cracked were replaced.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] On 8 February 2012, the checks were extended to cover all 68 A380 aircraft in operation.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The problem was considered to be minor and is not expected to affect operations.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] EADS acknowledged that the cost of repairs would be over $130 million, to be borne by Airbus.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The company said the problem was traced to stress and material used for the fittings.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Additionally, major airlines were seeking compensation from Airbus for revenue lost as a result of the cracks and subsequent grounding of fleets.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Airbus switched to a different type of aluminium alloy so aircraft delivered from 2014 onwards should not have this problem.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Around 2014, Airbus changed about 10% of all A380 doors, as some leaked during flight.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] One occurrence resulted in dropped oxygen masks and an emergency landing.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The switch was estimated to cost over €100 million.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Airbus stated that safety was sufficient, as the air pressure pushed the door into the frame.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] At the July 2016 Farnborough Airshow, Airbus announced that in a "prudent, proactive step", starting in 2018, it expected to deliver 12 A380 aircraft per year, down from 27 deliveries in 2015.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The firm also warned production might slip back into red ink (be unprofitable) on each aircraft produced at that time, though it anticipated production would remain in the black (profitable) for 2016 and 2017.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] As Airbus expected to build 15 airliners in 2017 and 12 in 2018, Airbus Commercial Aircraft president Fabrice Brégier said that, without orders in 2017, production would be reduced to below one per month while remaining profitable per unit and allowing the programme to continue for 20 to 30 years.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] In its 2017 half-year report, Airbus adjusted 2019 deliveries to eight aircraft.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] In November 2017, its chief executive Tom Enders was confident Airbus would still produce A380s in 2027 with more sales to come, and would further develop it to keep it competitive beyond 2030.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Airbus was profitable at a rate of 15 per year and was trying to drive breakeven down further but expected to take losses at eight per year.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] If it had failed to win the Emirates order, Airbus claimed that it was ready to phase out its production gradually as it fulfilled remaining orders until the early 2020s.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] In January 2018, Emirates confirmed the order for 36 A380s, but the deal was thrown back into question in October 2018 over a disagreement regarding engine fuel burn.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] To extend the programme, Airbus offered China a production role in early 2018.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] While state-owned Chinese airlines could order A380s, it would not help their low yield, as it lowered frequency; they did not need more volume as widebody aircraft were already used on domestic routes and using the A380 on its intended long-haul missions would free only a few airport slots.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] As of February 2018, Enders was confident the A380 would gain additional orders from existing or new operators, and saw opportunities in Asia and particularly in China where it was "under-represented".
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] In 2019, Lufthansa had retired 6 of its 14 A380s due to their unprofitability.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Later that year, Qatar Airways announced a switch from the A380 to the Boeing 777X starting from 2024.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] In February 2019, Airbus announced it would end A380 production by 2021, after its main customer, Emirates, agreed to drop an order for 39 of the aircraft, replacing it with 40 A330-900s and 30 A350-900s.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] At the time of the announcement, Airbus had 17 more A380s on its order book to complete before closing the production line – 14 for Emirates and three for All Nippon Airways – taking the total number of expected deliveries of the aircraft type to 251.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Airbus would have needed more than $90 million profit from the sale of each aircraft to cover the estimated $25 billion development cost of the programme.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] However, the $445 million price tag of each aircraft was not sufficient to even cover the production cost.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] With orders decreasing, the decision was made to cease production.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] One reason that the A380 did not achieve commercial viability for Airbus has been attributed to its extremely large capacity being optimised for a hub-and-spoke system, which was projected by Airbus to be thriving when the programme was conceived.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] However, airlines underwent a fundamental transition to a point-to-point system, which gets customers to their destination in one flight instead of two or three flights.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The massive scale of the A380 design was able to achieve a very low cost for passenger seat-distance, but efficiency within the hub-and-spoke paradigm was not able to overcome the efficiency of fewer flights required in the point-to-point system.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Consequently, orders for VLAs slowed in the mid-2010s, as widebody twin jets now offer similar range and greater fuel efficiency, giving airlines more flexibility at a lower upfront cost.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] For this reason, the Airbus A380 could not rely on freight orders for its continued production after demand for its passenger version waned (a factor which extended the 747's production by six years).
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] As an example of the A380's passenger-oriented design, the cockpit is located adjacent to the lower deck, and the upper deck flooring forms part of the plane's load-bearing structure.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Both of these factors preclude a freighter A380's ability to carry oversize loads, as it can neither be installed with a hinged nose at the front (as on the 747) nor have the upper deck flooring removed to form a singular cargo deck with a high ceiling.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] On 25 September 2020, Airbus completed assembly of the final A380 fuselage.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Nine aircraft remained to be delivered (eight for Emirates, one for All Nippon Airways) and production operations continued to finish those aircraft.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] On 17 March 2021, the final Airbus A380 (manufacturing serial number 272) made its maiden flight from Toulouse to Hamburg for cabin outfitting, before being delivered to Emirates on 16 December 2021.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The A380 was initially offered in two models: the *A380-800* and the *A380F*.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The A380-800's original configuration carried 555 passengers in a three-class configuration or 853 passengers (538 on the main deck and 315 on the upper deck) in a single-class economy configuration.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] In May 2007, Airbus began marketing a configuration with 30 fewer passengers (525 total in three classes) – traded for 200 nmi; 230 mi (370 km) more range – to better reflect trends in premium-class accommodation.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The design range for the A380−800 model is 8,500 nmi (15,700 km); capable of flying from Hong Kong to New York or from Sydney to Istanbul non-stop.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Freighter development was put on hold as Airbus prioritised the passenger version, and all orders for freighters were cancelled.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Other proposed variants included an *A380-900* stretch – seating about 656 passengers (or up to 960 passengers in an all-economy configuration) – and an extended-range version with the same passenger capacity as the A380-800.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The A380 is offered with the Rolls-Royce Trent 900 (A380-841/-842) or the Engine Alliance GP7000 (A380-861) turbofan engines.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The Trent 900 is a combination of the 3 m (118 in) fan and scaled intermediate pressure compressor of the Trent 8104 proposed for the Boeing 777-200LR/300ER (which was itself derived from the Boeing 777-200/200ER/300's Trent 800), and the Airbus A340-500/600's Trent 500 core.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The GP7200's high-pressure core is derived from GE's GE90 and its low-pressure sections are based on the PW4000 expertise.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Due to its modern engines and aerodynamic improvements, Lufthansa's A380s produce half the noise of the Boeing 747-200 while carrying 160 more passengers.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] In 2012, the A380 received an award from the Noise Abatement Society.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] London Heathrow is a key destination for the A380.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The aircraft is below the QC/2 departure and QC/0.5 arrival noise limits under the Quota Count system set by the airport.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Field measurements suggest the approach quota allocation for the A380 may be excessively generous compared to the older Boeing 747, but still quieter.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Rolls-Royce is supporting the CAA in understanding the relatively high A380/Trent 900 monitored noise levels.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Due to Heathrow's landing charges having a noise component, the A380 is cheaper to land there than a Boeing 777-200 and -300 and it saves $4,300 to $5,200 (2017 prices) per landing, or $15.3M to $18.8M (2017 prices) of present value over 15 years.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Tokyo Narita has a similar noise charge.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The A380 has thrust reversers on the inboard engines only.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The outboard engines lack them, reducing the amount of debris stirred up during landing.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The combination of wheel braking and large spoilers and flaps reduces the aircraft's reliance on thrust reversal.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The reversers are electrically actuated to save weight, and for greater reliability than pneumatic or hydraulic equivalents.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Having reversers on only two engines also saves a great deal of maintenance expense for operators as well as avoiding unnecessary weight to the outboard engines.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The A380's wings are built for a maximum takeoff weight (MTOW) over 600 tonnes to accommodate larger variants – the A380F freighter would require added internal strengthening.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The optimal wingspan for such an MTOW is about 90 m (300 ft) but airport restrictions of 80 m (260 ft) force the A380 to compensate with a longer chord for an aspect ratio of 7.8.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] This suboptimal aspect ratio reduces fuel efficiency by about 10% and increases operating costs several per cent, considering fuel costs constitute about 50% of the cost of long-haul aeroplane operation.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The common wing design approach sacrifices fuel efficiency on the A380-800 passenger model in particular because its lower MTOW allows for a higher aspect ratio with a shorter chord or thinner wing.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Still, Airbus estimated that the A380's size and advanced technology would provide lower operating costs per passenger than the 747-400.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The wings incorporate wingtip fences that extend above and below the wing surface, similar to those on the A310 and A320.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] These increase fuel efficiency and range by reducing induced drag.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The wingtip fences also reduce wake turbulence, which endangers following aircraft.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The wings of the A380 were designed in Filton, England and Wichita, US, with its manufacturing in Broughton in the United Kingdom.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The wings were then transported to the harbour of Mostyn, where they were transported by barge to Toulouse, France, for integration and final assembly with the rest of the aircraft and its components.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Singapore Airlines describes the A380's landing speed of 130–135 kn (240–250 km/h) as "impressively slow".
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] While most of the fuselage is made of aluminium alloys, composite materials comprise more than 20% of the A380's airframe.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Carbon-fibre reinforced plastic, glass-fibre reinforced plastic and quartz-fibre reinforced plastic are used extensively in wings, fuselage sections (such as the undercarriage and rear end of fuselage), tail surfaces, and doors.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The A380 is the first commercial airliner to have a central wing box made of carbon–fibre reinforced plastic.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] It is also the first to have a smoothly contoured wing cross–section.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The wings of other commercial airliners are partitioned span-wise into sections.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] This flowing continuous cross section reduces aerodynamic drag.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Thermoplastics are used in the leading edges of the slats.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The hybrid fibre metal laminate material GLARE (glass laminate aluminium reinforced epoxy) is used in the upper fuselage and on the stabilisers' leading edges.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] This aluminium-glass-fibre laminate is lighter and has better corrosion and impact resistance than conventional aluminium alloys used in aviation.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Unlike earlier composite materials, GLARE can be repaired using conventional aluminium repair techniques.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Newer weldable aluminium alloys are used in the A380's airframe.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] This enabled the widespread use of laser beam welding manufacturing techniques, eliminating rows of rivets and resulting in a lighter, stronger structure.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] High-strength aluminium (type 7449) reinforced with carbon fibre was used in the wing brackets of the first 120 A380s to reduce weight, but cracks were discovered and newer sets of the more critical brackets are made of standard aluminium 7010, increasing weight by 90 kg (198 lb).
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Repair costs for earlier aircraft were expected to be around €500 million (US$629 million).
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The paint is five layers thick and weighs about 650 kg (1,433 lb) when dry.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The A380 employs an integrated modular avionics (IMA) architecture, first used in advanced military aircraft, such as the Lockheed Martin F-22 Raptor, Lockheed Martin F-35 Lightning II, and Dassault Rafale.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The main IMA systems on the A380 were developed by the Thales Group.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Designed and developed by Airbus, Thales and Diehl Aerospace, the IMA suite was first used on the A380.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The suite is a technological innovation, with networked computing modules to support different applications.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The data networks use Avionics Full-Duplex Switched Ethernet, an implementation of ARINC 664.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] These are switched, full-duplex, star-topology and based on 100baseTX fast-Ethernet.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] This reduces the amount of wiring required and minimises latency.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Airbus used similar cockpit layout, procedures and handling characteristics to other Airbus aircraft, reducing crew training costs.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The A380 has an improved glass cockpit, using fly-by-wire flight controls linked to side-sticks.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The cockpit has eight 15 by 20 cm (5.9 by 7.9 in) liquid crystal displays, all physically identical and interchangeable; comprising two primary flight displays, two navigation displays, one engine parameter display, one system display and two multi-function displays.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The MFDs were introduced on the A380 to provide an easy-to-use interface to the flight management system – replacing three multifunction control and display units.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] They include QWERTY keyboards and trackballs, interfacing with a graphical "point-and-click" display system.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The Network Systems Server (NSS) is the heart of A380s paperless cockpit; it eliminates bulky manuals and traditional charts.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The NSS has enough inbuilt robustness to eliminate onboard backup paper documents.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The A380s network and server system stores data and offers electronic documentation, providing a required equipment list, navigation charts, performance calculations, and an aircraft logbook.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] This is accessed through the MFDs and controlled via the keyboard interface.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Power-by-wire flight control actuators have been used for the first time in civil aviation to back up primary hydraulic actuators.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Also, during certain manoeuvres they augment the primary actuators.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] They have self-contained hydraulic and electrical power supplies.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Electro-hydrostatic actuators (EHA) are used in the aileron and elevator, electric and hydraulic motors to drive the slats as well as electrical backup hydrostatic actuators (EBHA) for the rudder and some spoilers.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The A380's 350 bar (35 MPa or 5,000 psi) hydraulic system is a significant difference from the typical 210 bar (21 MPa or 3,000 psi) hydraulics used on most commercial aircraft since the 1940s.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] First used in military aircraft, high-pressure hydraulics reduce the weight and size of pipelines, actuators and related components.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The 350 bar pressure is generated by eight de-clutchable hydraulic pumps.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The hydraulic lines are typically made from titanium; the system features both fuel- and air-cooled heat exchangers.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Self-contained electrically powered hydraulic power packs serve as backups for the primary systems, instead of a secondary hydraulic system, saving weight and reducing maintenance.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The A380 uses four 150 kVA variable-frequency electrical generators, eliminating constant-speed drives and improving reliability.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The A380 uses aluminium power cables instead of copper for weight reduction.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The electrical power system is fully computerised and many contactors and breakers have been replaced by solid-state devices for better performance and increased reliability.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The auxiliary power comprises the Auxiliary Power Unit (APU), the electronic control box (ECB), and mounting hardware.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The APU in use on the A380 is the 1,300 kW PW 980A APU.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The APU primarily provides air to power the Air Generation System (AGS) on the ground and to start the engines.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The AGS provides cooling and heating inside the aircraft.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The APU also powers two 120 kVA electric generators that provide auxiliary electric power to the aircraft.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] There is also a ram air turbine (RAT) with a 70 kVA generator.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The A380-800's cabin has 550 square metres (5,920 sq ft) of usable floor space, 40% more than the next largest airliner, the Boeing 747-8.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The cabin has features to reduce traveller fatigue such as a quieter interior and higher pressurisation than previous generations of aircraft; the A380 is pressurised to the equivalent altitude of 1,520 m (5,000 ft) up to 12,000 m (39,000 ft).
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] It has 50% less cabin noise, 50% more cabin area and volume, larger windows, bigger overhead bins, and 60 cm (2.0 ft) more headroom than the 747-400.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Seating options range from 3-room 12 m2 (130 sq ft) "residence" in first class to 11-across in economy.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] A380 economy seats are up to 48 cm (19 in) wide in a 10-abreast configuration, compared with the 10-abreast configuration on the 747-400 that typically has seats 44.5 cm (17.5 in) wide.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] On other aircraft, economy seats range from 41.5 to 52.3 cm (16.3 to 20.6 in) in width.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The A380's upper and lower decks are connected by two stairways, one fore and one aft, both wide enough to accommodate two passengers side by side; this cabin arrangement allows multiple seat configurations.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The maximum certified carrying capacity is 853 passengers in an all-economy-class layout, Airbus lists the "typical" three-class layout as accommodating 525 passengers, with 10 first, 76 business, and 439 economy class seats.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Airline configurations range from Korean Air's 407 passengers to Emirates' two-class 615 seats and average around 480–490 seats.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Air Austral's proposed 840 passenger layout has not come to fruition.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The A380's interior illumination system uses bulbless LEDs in the cabin, cockpit, and cargo decks.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The LEDs in the cabin can be altered to create an ambience simulating daylight, night, or intermediate levels.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] On the outside of the aircraft, HID lighting is used for brighter illumination.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Airbus's publicity has stressed the comfort and space of the A380 cabin, and advertised onboard relaxation areas such as bars, beauty salons, duty-free shops, and restaurants.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Proposed amenities resembled those installed on earlier airliners, particularly 1970s wide-body jets, which largely gave way to regular seats for greater passenger capacity.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Airbus has acknowledged that some cabin proposals were unlikely to be installed, and that it was ultimately the airlines' decision how to configure the interior.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Industry analysts suggested that implementing customisation has slowed the production speeds, and raised costs.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Due to delivery delays, Singapore Airlines and Air France debuted their seat designs on different aircraft prior to the A380.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Initial operators typically configured their A380s for three-class service, while adding extra features for passengers in premium cabins.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Launch customer Singapore Airlines introduced partly enclosed first-class suites on its A380s in 2007, each featuring a leather seat with a separate bed; center suites could be joined to create a double bed.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] A year later, Qantas debuted a new first-class seat-bed and a sofa lounge at the front of the upper deck on its A380s, and in 2009, Air France unveiled an upper deck electronic art gallery.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] In late 2008, Emirates introduced "shower spas" in first class on its A380s allowing each first class passenger five minutes of hot water, drawing on 2.5 tonnes of water, although only 60% of it was used.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Etihad Airways and Qatar Airways also have a bar lounge and seating area on the upper deck, while Etihad has enclosed areas for two people each.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] In addition to lounge areas, some A380 operators have installed amenities consistent with other aircraft in their respective fleets, including self-serve snack bars, premium economy sections, and redesigned business-class seating.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The Hamburg Aircraft Interiors Expo in April 2015 saw the presentation of an 11-seat row economy cabin for the A380.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Airbus is reacting to a changing economy; the recession which began in 2008 saw a drop in market percentage of first class and business seats to six per cent and an increase in budget economy travellers.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Among other causes is the reluctance of employers to pay for executives to travel in First or Business Class.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Airbus' chief of cabin marketing, Ingo Wuggestzer, told *Aviation Week and Space Technology* that the standard three-class cabin no longer reflected market conditions.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The 11-seat row on the A380 is accompanied by similar options on other widebodies: nine across on the Airbus A330 and ten across on the A350.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] In the 1990s, aircraft manufacturers were planning to introduce larger planes than the Boeing 747.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] In a common effort of the International Civil Aviation Organization (ICAO) with manufacturers, airports and its member agencies, the "80-metre box" was created, the airport gates allowing planes up to 80 m (260 ft) wingspan and length to be accommodated.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Airbus designed the A380 according to these guidelines, and to operate safely on Group V runways and taxiways with a 60 metres (200 ft) loadbearing width.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The US FAA initially opposed this, then in July 2007, the FAA and EASA agreed to let the A380 operate on 45 m (148 ft) runways without restrictions.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The A380-800 is approximately 30% larger in overall size than the 747-400.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Runway lighting and signage may need changes to provide clearance to the wings and avoid blast damage from the engines.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Runways, runway shoulders and taxiway shoulders may be required to be stabilised to reduce the likelihood of foreign object damage caused to (or by) the outboard engines, which are more than 25 m (82 ft) from the centre line of the aircraft, compared to 21 m (69 ft) for the 747-400, and 747-8.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Airbus measured pavement loads using a 540-tonne (595 short tons) ballasted test rig, designed to replicate the landing gear of the A380.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The rig was towed over a section of pavement at Airbus's facilities that had been instrumented with embedded load sensors.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] It was determined that the pavement of most runways will not need to be reinforced despite the higher weight, as it is distributed on more wheels than in other passenger aircraft with a total of 22 wheels (that is, its ground pressure is lower).
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The A380 undercarriage consists of four main landing gear legs and one noseleg (a layout similar to that of the 747), with the two inboard landing gear legs each supporting six wheels.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The A380 requires service vehicles with lifts capable of reaching the upper deck, as well as tractors capable of handling the A380's maximum ramp weight.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] When using two jetway bridges the boarding time is 45 min, and when using an extra jetway to the upper deck it is reduced to 34 min.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The A380 has an airport turnaround time of 90–110 minutes.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] In 2008, the A380 test aircraft were used to trial the modifications made to several airports to accommodate the type.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] As of 2023, the A380 is the only aircraft in wake turbulence category Super (J).
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] As the A380 fleet grows older, airworthiness authority rules require certain scheduled inspections from approved aircraft tool shops.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] The increasing fleet size (at the time projected to reach 286 aircraft in 2020) cause expected maintenance and modification to cost $6.8 billion for 2015–2020, of which $2.1 billion are for engines.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] Emirates performed its first 3C-check for 55 days in 2014.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p01] During lengthy shop stays, some airlines will use the opportunity to install new interiors.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] Singapore Airlines flew the inaugural commercial flight from Singapore to Sydney on 25 October 2007.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] In February 2009, the one millionth passenger was flown with Singapore Airlines and by May of that year 1,500,000 passengers had flown on 4,200 flights.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] Air France received its first A380 in October 2009.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] Lufthansa received its first A380 in May 2010.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] By July 2010, the 31 A380s then in service had transported 6 million passengers on 17,000 flights between 20 international destinations.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] Airbus delivered the 100th A380 on 14 March 2013 to Malaysia Airlines.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] In June 2014, over 65 million passengers had flown the A380, and more than 100 million passengers (averaging 375 per flight) by September 2015, with an availability of 98.5%.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] In 2014, Emirates stated that its A380 fleet had load factors of 90–100%, and that the popularity of the aircraft with its passengers had not decreased in the past year.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] On 16 December 2021, their largest customer, Emirates, received its 123rd A380 in Hamburg, which was the 251st and the last Superjumbo delivered by Airbus.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] The airline's strategy has enabled A380 teams to develop new innovations on an ongoing basis and improve the aircraft's operational performance by up to 99.3%, a level never seen before on a quadjet airliner.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] Many of the innovations developed on the Emirates A380 cabin were a first for Airbus, such as the first class showers, lighting scenarios, and the recent premium economy cabin.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] By December 2021, the global A380 fleet had carried over 300 million passengers to more than 70 destinations and completed more than 800,000 flights over 7.3 million block hours with 99 per cent operational reliability and no hull-loss accidents.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] Over 50% of the fleet's capacity is from, to, or within the Asia-Pacific region, of which around 15% is on regional flights within Asia (OAG 2017).
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] While the A380-800 was the only model put into production, other variants were proposed that might have made the design more appealing in shifting market conditions.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] Airbus offered a cargo aircraft variant, called the *A380F*, since at least June 2005, capable of transporting a 150 t (330,000 lb) maximum payload over a 5,600 nmi (10,400 km; 6,400 mi) range.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] It would have had 7% better payload and better range than the Boeing 747-8F, but also higher trip costs.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] It would have the largest payload capacity of any freighter aircraft except the Antonov An-225 Mriya.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] Production was suspended until the A380 production lines had settled, with no firm availability date.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] The A380F was displayed on the Airbus website until at least January 2013, but was not any more in April.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] A patent for a "combi" version was applied for.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] This version would offer the flexibility of carrying both passengers and cargo, along with being rapidly reconfigurable to expand or contract the cargo area and passenger area as needed for a given flight.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] At launch in December 2000, a 656-seat A380-200 was proposed as a derivative of the 555-seat baseline, called the *A380 Stretch*.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] In November 2007, Airbus top sales executive and chief operating officer John Leahy confirmed plans for another enlarged variant – the A380-900 – with more seating space than the A380-800.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] The A380-900 would have had a seating capacity for 650 passengers in standard configuration and for approximately 900 passengers in an economy-only configuration.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] Airlines that expressed an interest in the A380-900 included Emirates, Virgin Atlantic, Cathay Pacific, Air France, KLM, Lufthansa, Kingfisher Airlines, and leasing company ILFC.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] In May 2010, Airbus announced that A380-900 development would be postponed until production of the A380-800 stabilised.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] On 11 December 2014, at the annual Airbus Investor Day forum, Airbus CEO Fabrice Brégier controversially announced, "We will one day launch an A380neo and one day launch a stretched A380".
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] This statement followed speculation sparked by Airbus CFO Harald Wilhelm that Airbus could possibly axe the A380 ahead of its time due to softening demand.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] On 15 June 2015, John Leahy, Airbus's chief operating officer for customers, stated that Airbus was again looking at the A380-900 programme.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] Airbus's newest concept would be a stretch of the A380-800 offering 50 seats more – not 100 seats as originally envisaged.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] This stretch would be tied to a potential re-engining of the A380-800.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] According to Flight Global, an A380-900 would make better use of the A380's existing wing.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] On 15 June 2015, Reuters reported that Airbus was discussing an improved and stretched version of the A380 with at least six customers.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] The aircraft, called the *A380neo*, featured new engines and would accommodate an additional fifty passengers.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] Deliveries to customers were planned for sometime in 2020 or 2021.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] On 19 July 2015, Airbus CEO Fabrice Brégier stated that the company would have built a new version of the A380 featuring new improved wings and new engines.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] Speculation about the development of a so-called A380neo ("neo" for "new engine option") had been going on for a few months after earlier press releases in 2014, and in 2015, the company was considering whether to end production of the type prior to 2018 or develop a new A380 variant.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] Later it was revealed that Airbus had been looking at both the possibility of a longer A380 in line of the previously planned A380-900 and a new engine version, i.e.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] Brégier also revealed that the new variant would be planned to enter service by 2020.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] The engine would most likely had been one of a variety of all-new options from Rolls-Royce, ranging from derivatives of the A350's XWB-84/97 to the future Advance project due at around 2020.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] On 3 June 2016, Emirates President Tim Clark stated that talks between Emirates and Airbus on the A380neo had "lapsed".
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] On 12 June 2017, Fabrice Brégier confirmed that Airbus would not launch an A380neo, stating "...there is no business case to do that, this is absolutely clear." However, Brégier stated it would not stop Airbus from looking at what could be done to improve the performance of the aircraft.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] One such proposal was a 32 ft (9.8 m) wingspan extension to reduce drag and increase fuel efficiency by 4%, though further increase was likely to be seen on the aircraft with new Sharklets like on the A380plus.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] Tim Clark stated the proposed re-engining would have offered a 12–14% fuel-burn reduction with an enhanced Trent XWB.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] In June 2023, despite A380 production having ceased, Clark renewed his plea for a re-engined A380neo, suggesting that a next-generation Rolls-Royce UltraFan could give a 25% reduction in fuel burn and emissions.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] The A380plus' maximum takeoff weight would have been increased by 3 t (6,600 lb) to 578 t (1,274,000 lb), allowing it to carry more passengers over the same 8,200 nmi (15,200 km; 9,400 mi) range or increase the range by 300 nmi (560 km; 350 mi).
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] Winglet mockups, 4.7 m (15 ft 5 in) high, were displayed on the MSN04 test aircraft at Le Bourget.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] Wing twist would have been modified and camber changed by increasing its height by 33 millimetres (1+1⁄4 in) between Rib 10 and Rib 30, along with upper-belly fairing improvements.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] The in-flight entertainment, the flight management system and the fuel pumps would be from the A350 to reduce weight and improve reliability and fuel economy.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] Light checks for the A380plus would be required after 1,000 h instead of 750 h and heavy check downtime would be reduced to keep the aircraft flying for six days more per year.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] In its 2000 Global Market Forecast, Airbus estimated demand for Very Large Aircraft (VLA) with more than 400 seats at 1,235: 360 up to 2009 and 875 by 2019.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] In late 2003, Boeing forecast 320 "Boeing 747 and larger" passenger aircraft over 20 years, close to the 298 orders actually placed for the A380 and 747-8 passenger airliners as of March 2020.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] In 2007, Airbus estimated demand for 1,283 VLAs in the following 20 years if airport congestion remains constant, up to 1,771 VLAs if congestion increases, with most deliveries (56%) in Asia-Pacific, and 415 very large, 120-tonne plus freighters.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] For the same period, Boeing was estimating the demand for 590 large (747 or A380) passenger airliners and 630 freighters.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] Estimates for the total over a twenty-year period have varied from 400 to over 1,700.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] In 2013, Cathay Pacific and Singapore Airlines needed to balance frequency and capacity.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] China Southern struggled for two years to use its A380s from Beijing, and finally received Boeing 787s in its base in Guangzhou, but where it cannot command a premium, unlike Beijing or Shanghai.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] In 2013, Air France withdrew A380 services to Singapore and Montreal and switched to smaller aircraft.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] In 2014, British Airways replaced three 777 flights between London and Los Angeles with two A380 per day.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] Emirates' Tim Clark saw a large potential for East Asian A380-users, and criticised Airbus' marketing efforts.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] At the A380 launch, most Europe-Asia and transpacific routes used Boeing 747-400s at fairly low frequencies but, since then, routes proliferated with open skies, and most airlines downsized, offering higher frequencies and more routes.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] The huge capacity offered by each flight eroded the yield: North America was viewed as 17% of the market but the A380 never materialised as a 747 replacement, with only 15 747s remaining in passenger service in November 2017 for transpacific routes, where time zones restrict potential frequency.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] Consolidation changed the networks, and major US airlines constrained capacity and emphasised daily frequencies for business traffic with midsize widebodies like the 787, to extract higher yields; the focus being on profits, with market share ceded to Asian carriers.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] The 747 was largely replaced on transatlantic flights by the 767, and on the transpacific flights by the 777; newer, smaller aircraft with similar seat-mile costs have lower trip costs and allow more direct routes.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] Cabin 'densification', to lower unit costs, could aggravate this overcapacity.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] In 2005, 270 sales were necessary to attain break-even and with 751 expected deliveries its internal rate of return outlook was at 19%, but due to disruptions in the ramp-up leading to overcosts and delayed deliveries, it increased to 420 in 2006.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] In 2010, EADS CFO Hans Peter Ring said that break-even could be achieved by 2015 when 200 deliveries were projected.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] In 2012, Airbus clarified that the aircraft production costs would be less than its sales price.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] On 11 December 2014, Airbus chief financial officer Harald Wilhelm hinted the possibility of ending the programme in 2018, disappointing Emirates president Tim Clark.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] Airbus responded to the protests by playing down the possibility the A380 would be abandoned, instead emphasising that enhancing the aeroplane was a likelier scenario.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] On 22 December 2014, as the A380 was about to break even, Airbus CEO Fabrice Brégier ruled out cancelling it.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] Ten years after its first flight, Brégier said it was "almost certainly introduced ten years too early".
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] While no longer losing money on each plane sold, Airbus admits that the company would never recoup the $25 billion investment it made in the project.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] Airbus' 2017 demand forecast was still for 1,400 VLAs over a 20-year period.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] The company aimed to secure a 50% share, up to 700 units.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] Instead, it delivered 215 aircraft in 10 years, achieving three produced per month but not the four per month target.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] Boeing saw the VLA market as too small to retain in its 2017 forecast.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] Richard Aboulafia predicted a 2020 final delivery, with losses due to "hubris, shoddy market analysis, nationalism and simple wishful thinking".
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] In 2017, the A380 fleet exceeded the number of remaining passenger Boeing 747s, which had declined from 740 aircraft when the A380 was launched in 2000 to 550 units when the A380 was introduced in 2007, and around 200 ten years later.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] By the 2020s, the market-share battle had shifted to large single-aisle planes and 300-seat twin-aisle planes.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] As of 2016, the list price of an A380 was US$432.6 million.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] Negotiated discounts made the actual prices much lower, and industry experts questioned whether the A380 project would ever pay for itself.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] The first aircraft was sold and leased back by Singapore Airlines in 2007 to Dr.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] In 2016, IAG's Willie Walsh said he could add a few, but also that he found the price of new aircraft "outrageous" and would source them from the second-hand market.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] AirInsight estimates its hourly cost at $26,000, or around $50 per seat hour (when configured for only 520 seats), which compares to $44 per seat hour for a Boeing 777-300ER, and $90 per seat hour for a Boeing 747-400 as of November 2015.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] The A380 was designed with large wing and tail surfaces to accommodate a planned stretch; this resulted in a high empty weight per seat.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] The stretch never occurred to take advantage of this, and the A380's cost-per-seat is expected to be matched by the A350-1000 and 777-9.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] With a theoretical maximum seating capacity of 853 seats, which is not used by any airline, the Airbus A380 consumes 2.4 litres of kerosene per 100 passenger kilometres.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] This increases with a reduced seating capacity from 555 to 3.5 l/100 pkm and is 5.2 litres of kerosene per 100 passenger kilometres in the smallest possible variant with only 362 seats.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] As of 2015, several airlines expressed their interest in selling their aircraft, partially coinciding with expiring lease contracts for the aircraft.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] Several in-service A380s were offered for lease to other airlines.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] After Malaysia Airlines was unable to sell or lease its six A380s, it decided to refurbish the aircraft with seating for 700 and transfer them to a subsidiary carrier for religious pilgrimage flights.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] As it started receiving its six A350s to replace its A380s in December 2017, the new subsidiary will serve the Hajj and Umrah market with them, starting in the third quarter of 2018 and could be expanded above six beyond 2020 to 2022.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] The cabin will have 36 business seats and 600 economy seats, with a 712-seat reconfiguration possible within five days.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] The fleet could be chartered half the year for the tourism industry like cruise shipping and will be able to operate for the next 40 years if oil prices stay low.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] As they should be parked by June 2018 before reconfiguration, MAS confirmed the plans and will also use them for peak periods to high traffic markets like London.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] In August 2017, it was announced that Hi Fly would lease two used aircraft.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] The Portuguese ACMI/charter airline will use the aircraft for markets where high capacity is needed and airports where slots are scarce.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] The first aircraft was scheduled to begin commercial operations during the first quarter of 2018 Hi Fly was to receive its A380s from mid 2018 in a 471-seat configuration: 399 on the main deck, 60 business-class and 12 first-class seats on the upper deck, the Singapore Airlines layout.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] Hi Fly first used one of their A380s on 1 August 2018 for a one-off flight to enable Thomas Cook Airlines to repatriate passengers from Rhodes to Copenhagen following IT problems in the Greek airport.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] As of December 2019, Hi Fly has leased one used A380.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] Amedeo, mainly an A380 lessor and the largest with 22, mostly leased to Emirates, wants to find a use for them after their lease expires from 2022, and study if there is a demand to wet lease them.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] Swiss aircraft broker Sparfell & Partners plans to convert for head-of-state or VVIP transport some of Dr.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] Peters' four ex-SIA A380s for under $300 million apiece, less than a new Boeing 777 or Airbus A330.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] As of November 2018, Air France was planning to return five of its A380s to lessors by the end of 2019 and refurbish its other five with new interiors by 2020 for $51 million per aircraft.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] By July 2019, Air France revised this plan and intended to phase out all ten of its A380s by 2022 as part of an "accelerated" retirement plan, replacing them with no more than nine twin-engined wide-body aircraft.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] The A330-900, A350-900 and 787-9 were being evaluated as potential replacements.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] Following the cancellation of the programme in February 2019, the residual value of existing aircraft is in doubt.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] While Amedeo argued that cancellation should benefit the value, this will depend on whether any new airlines are prepared to adopt second-hand A380s, and how many existing users continue to operate the aircraft.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] Even the teardown value is questionable, in that the engines, usually the most valuable part of a scrap aircraft, are not used by any other models.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] With four A380s leased to Singapore Airlines having been returned between October 2017 and March 2018, Dr.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] Peters feared a weak aftermarket and is considering scrapping them, although they are on sale for a business jet conversion, but on the other hand Airbus sees a potential for African airlines and Chinese airlines, Hajj charters and its large Gulf operators.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] In 2017 a parted out A380 was worth between $30 million to $50 million if it is at half-life.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] Teardown specialists have declined offers for several aircraft at part-out prices due to high risk as a secondary market is uncertain with $30 to $40 million for the refurbishment, but should be between $20 and $30 million to be viable.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] When the aircraft were proposed to British Airways, Hi Fly and Iran Air, BA were unwilling to replace its Boeing 747s until 2021, while Iran Air faced political uncertainty and Hi Fly did not have a convincing business case.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] Peters recommended to its investors on 28 June 2018 to sell the aircraft parts with VAS Aero Services within two years for US$45 million, quickly for components like the landing gear or the APU.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] Rolls-Royce Trent 900 leasing beyond March 2019 were predicted to generate US$480,000 monthly for each aircraft before selling the turbofans by 2020.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] With a total revenue of US$80 million per aircraft, the overall return expected is 145–155% while 72% and 81% of their debt had already been repaid.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] The fifth plane coming back from SIA, owned by Doric, has been leased by Hi Fly Malta with a lease period of "nearly 6 years".
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] Hi Fly Malta became the first operator of second-hand A380 (MSN006).
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] Norwegian Long Haul briefly leased Hi Fly Malta A380 in August 2018, which operated the aircraft following engine problems with their Dreamliner fleet.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] Norwegian leased the A380 again in late 2018 to help deal with the passenger backlog as a result of the Gatwick Airport drone incident.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] Two others returned from Singapore Airlines in the coming weeks (June 2018) but they could stay with an existing Asian A380 flag carrier.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] The teardown value includes $32–$33 million from the engines in 2020 and $4 million from leasing them until then, while the value of a 2008 A380 would be $78.4 million in 2020 and its monthly lease in 2018 would be $929,000.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] The two aircraft have returned 3.8–4.2% per year since 2008 but the 145–155% return is lower than the 220% originally forecast.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] Of the nearly 500 made, 50 747-400s were sold in the secondary market, including only 25 to new customers.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] These are among the first A380s delivered, lacking the improvements and weight savings of later ones.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] The first two A380s delivered to Singapore Airlines (MSN003 and MSN005) flew to Tarbes, France, to be scrapped.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] Their engines and some components were dismantled and removed, while the livery was painted over in white.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] As of September 2019, Emirates initiated its A380 retirement plan – which will see the type remain in service until at least 2035 – by retiring two aircraft that were due for a major overhaul, and using them as parts donors for the rest of the fleet.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] Emirates does not see any demand in the second-hand market, but is indifferent in that the retired aircraft have already been fully written down and thus have no residual value.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] As further aircraft are retired, Emirates-owned airframes will continue to be used for parts, while leased airframes will be returned to the lessors.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] One such return to lessor Doric was purchased by Emirates for £25.3 million in late 2022, as spare parts.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] Fourteen customers have ordered and taken delivery of the A380 as of April 2019.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] Total orders for the A380 stand at 251 as of November 2019.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] The biggest customer is Emirates, which has committed to order a total of 123 A380s as of 14 February 2019.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] One VIP order was made in 2007 but later cancelled by Airbus.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] The A380F version attracted 27 orders, before they were either cancelled (20) or converted to A380-800 (7) following the production delay and the subsequent suspension of the freighter programme.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] Delivery takes place in Hamburg for customers from Europe and the Middle East and in Toulouse for customers from the rest of the world.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] EADS explained that deliveries in 2013 were to be slowed temporarily to accommodate replacement of the wing rib brackets where cracks were detected earlier in the existing fleet.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] In 2013, in expectation of raising the number of orders placed, Airbus announced "attractable discounts" to airlines who placed large orders for the A380.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] Soon after, at the November 2013 Dubai Air Show, Emirates ordered 150 777X and Etihad Airways ordered 50 aircraft, totalling $20 billion.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] In late July 2014, Airbus announced that it had terminated five A380 firm orders from the Japanese low-cost carrier, Skymark Airlines, citing concerns over the airline's financial performance.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] In 2016, the largest Japanese carrier, All Nippon Airways (ANA), took over three of the orders and the remaining two that were already produced and put into long-term storage were taken up later by the main customer, Emirates.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] Qantas planned to order eight more aircraft but froze its order while the airline restructured its operations.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] Qantas eventually cancelled its order in February 2019 amid doubts over the A380's future.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] Amedeo, an aircraft lessor that ordered 20 A380s, had not found a client for the airliner and eventually cancelled their order in 2019.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] Virgin Atlantic ordered six A380s in 2001 but never took delivery and later cancelled them in 2018.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] In June 2017, Emirates had 48 orders outstanding, but due to lack of space in Dubai Airport, it deferred 12 deliveries by one year and would not take any in 2019–20 before replacing its early airliners from 2021.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] There were open production slots in 2019, and Airbus reduced its production rate in 2017–2018 at 12 per year.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] At its 100th delivery ceremony, Emirates CEO Ahmed bin Saeed Al Maktoum was hoping to order new A380s at the November 2017 Dubai Air Show.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] Emirates does not need the small front staircase and eleven-abreast economy of the A380plus concept, but wants Airbus to commit to continue production for at least 10 years.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] On 18 January 2018, Airbus secured a preliminary agreement from Emirates for up to 36 A380s, to be delivered from 2020, valued at $16 billion at list prices.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] The contract was signed in February 2018, comprising a firm order for 20 A380s and options on 16 more.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] In early 2019, Airbus confirmed it was in discussions with Emirates over its A380 contract.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] If the A380's only stable client were to drop the type, Airbus could cease production of the superjumbo.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] Emirates was at odds with Rolls-Royce over shortfalls in fuel savings from the Trent 900s, and could switch its order for 36 A380s to the smaller A350.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] The A350 could also replace its provisional order for 40 Boeing 787-10s, placed in 2017, as engine margins on the 787 are insufficient for the hot Dubai weather.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] On 14 February 2019, Emirates decided to cancel its order for 39 planes, opting to replace them with A350s and A330neos.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] Airbus stated that this cancellation would bring the A380's production to an end when the last unfilled orders are delivered in 2021.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] On 21 March 2019, All Nippon Airways received its first of three A380s painted with the Sea Turtle livery.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] Called the ANA Blue, this A380 will be used for 3 flights a week, going from Tokyo to Honolulu and back.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] In October 2021, Emirates announced it would receive its final three A380s to be delivered with the last aircraft in December 2021, ending production of the A380.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] There were 189 aircraft (of 251 delivered) in service with 12 operators as of May 2025, with Emirates being by far the largest operator with 116 A380s in its fleet.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airbus-a380-p02] Other top operators are British Airways (12), Singapore Airlines (12), and Qantas (10).
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] A moving aircraft including the jet engine or propeller causes compression and rarefaction of the air, producing motion of air molecules.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] This movement propagates through the air as pressure waves.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] If these pressure waves are strong enough and within the audible frequency spectrum, a sensation of hearing is produced.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] Different aircraft types have different noise levels and frequencies.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] Much of the noise in propeller aircraft comes equally from the propellers and aerodynamics.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] Helicopter noise is aerodynamically induced noise from the main and tail rotors and mechanically induced noise from the main gearbox and various transmission chains.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] The mechanical sources produce narrow band high intensity peaks relating to the rotational speed and movement of the moving parts.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] In computer modelling terms, noise from a moving aircraft can be treated as a line source.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] Aircraft gas turbine engines (jet engines) are responsible for much of the aircraft noise during takeoff and climb, such as the *buzzsaw noise* generated when the tips of the fan blades reach supersonic speeds.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] However, with advances in noise reduction technologies—the airframe is typically more noisy during landing.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] The majority of engine noise heard is due to jet noise—although high bypass-ratio turbofans do have considerable fan noise.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] The high velocity jet leaving the back of the engine has an inherent shear layer instability (if not thick enough) and rolls up into ring vortices.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] The Sound Pressure Level,SPL, associated with engine noise is proportional to the jet speed (to a high power).
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] Therefore, even modest reductions in exhaust velocity will produce a large reduction in jet noise.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] Engines are the main source of aircraft noise.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] The geared Pratt & Whitney PW1000G helped reduce the noise levels of the Bombardier CSeries, Mitsubishi MRJ and Embraer E-Jet E2 crossover narrowbody aircraft: the gearbox allows the fan to spin at an optimal speed, which is one third the speed of the LP turbine, for slower fan tip speeds.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] It has a 75% smaller noise footprint than current equivalents.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] The PowerJet SaM146 in the Sukhoi Superjet 100 features 3D aerodynamic fan blades and a nacelle with a long mixed duct flow nozzle to reduce noise.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] Aerodynamic noise arises from the airflow around the aircraft fuselage and control surfaces.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] This type of noise increases with aircraft speed and also at low altitudes due to the density of the air.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] Jet-powered aircraft create intense noise from aerodynamics.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] Low-flying, high-speed military aircraft produce especially loud aerodynamic noise.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] The shape of the nose, windshield or canopy of an aircraft affects the sound produced.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] Much of the noise of a propeller aircraft is of aerodynamic origin due to the flow of air around the blades.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] The helicopter main and tail rotors also give rise to aerodynamic noise.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] This type of aerodynamic noise is mostly low frequency determined by the rotor speed.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] Typically noise is generated when flow passes an object on the aircraft, for example, the wings or landing gear.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] Sonic booms due to large supersonic aircraft can be particularly loud and startling, tend to awaken people, and may cause minor damage to some structures.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] This led to the prohibition of routine supersonic flight overland.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] Although sonic booms cannot be completely prevented, research suggests that with careful shaping of the vehicle, the nuisance due to sonic booms may be reduced to the point that overland supersonic flight may become a feasible option.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] Cockpit and cabin pressurization and conditioning systems are often a major contributor within cabins of both civilian and military aircraft.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] Other internal aircraft systems can also contribute, such as specialized electronic equipment in some military aircraft.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] Aircraft engines are the major source of noise and can exceed 140 decibels (dB) during takeoff.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] While airborne, the main sources of noise are the engines and the high speed turbulence over the fuselage.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] There are health consequences of elevated sound levels.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] Elevated workplace or other noise can cause hearing impairment, hypertension, ischemic heart disease, annoyance, sleep disturbance, and decreased school performance.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] Although some hearing loss occurs naturally with age, in many developed nations the impact of noise is sufficient to impair hearing over the course of a lifetime.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] Elevated noise levels can create stress, increase workplace accident rates, and stimulate aggression and other anti-social behaviors.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] Airport noise has been linked to high blood pressure.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] Aircraft noise increases risks of heart attacks.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] A large-scale statistical analysis of the health effects of aircraft noise was undertaken in the late 2000s by Bernhard Greiser for the Umweltbundesamt, Germany's central environmental office.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] The health data of over one million residents around the Cologne airport were analysed for health effects correlating with aircraft noise.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] The results were then corrected for other noise influences in the residential areas, and for socioeconomic factors, to reduce possible skewing of the data.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] The German study concluded that aircraft noise clearly and significantly impairs health.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] For example, a day-time average sound pressure level of 60 decibels increased coronary heart disease by 61% in men and 80% in women.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] As another indicator, a night-time average sound pressure level of 55 decibels increased the risk of heart attacks by 66% in men and 139% in women.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] Statistically significant health effects did however start as early as from an average sound pressure level of 40 decibels.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] The Federal Aviation Administration (FAA) regulates the maximum noise level that individual civil aircraft can emit through requiring aircraft to meet certain noise certification standards.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] These standards designate changes in maximum noise level requirements by "stage" designation.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] The U.S. noise standards are defined in the Code of Federal Regulations (CFR) Title 14 Part 36 – Noise Standards: Aircraft Type and Airworthiness Certification (14 CFR Part 36).
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] The FAA says that a maximum day-night average sound level of 65 dB is incompatible with residential communities.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] Communities in affected areas may be eligible for mitigation such as soundproofing.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] Aircraft noise also affects people within the aircraft: crew and passengers.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] Cabin noise can be studied to address the occupational exposure and the health and safety of pilots and flight attendants.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] In 1998, 64 commercial airline pilots were surveyed regarding hearing loss and tinnitus.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] In 1999, the NIOSH conducted several noise surveys and health hazard evaluations, and found noise levels exceeding its recommended exposure limit of 85 A-weighted decibels as an 8-hr TWA.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] In 2006, the noise levels inside an Airbus A321 during cruise have been reported as approximately 78 dB(A) and during taxi when the aircraft engines are producing minimal thrust, noise levels in the cabin have been recorded at 65 dB(A).
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] In 2008, a study of Swedish airlines cabin crews found average sound levels between 78 and 84 dB(A) with maximum A-weighted exposure of 114 dB but found no major hearing threshold shifts.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] In 2018, a study of sound levels measured on 200 flights representing six aircraft groups found media noise level of 83.5 db(A) with levels reaching 110 dB(A) on certain flights, but only 4.5% exceeded the NIOSH recommended 8-hr TWA of 85 dB(A).
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] Simulated aircraft noise at 65 dB(A) has been shown to negatively affect individuals’ memory and recall of auditory information.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] A BAC of 0.10 is double the legal limit required to operate a motor vehicle in many developed countries such as Australia.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] In the United States, since aviation noise became a public issue in the late 1960s, governments have enacted legislative controls.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] Aircraft designers, manufacturers, and operators have developed quieter aircraft and better operating procedures.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] Modern high-bypass turbofan engines, for example, are notably more quiet than the turbojets and low-bypass turbofans of the 1960s.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] FAA Aircraft Certification achieved noise reductions classified as "Stage 3" aircraft; which has been upgraded to "Stage 4" noise certification resulting in quieter aircraft.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] This has resulted in lower noise exposures in spite of increased traffic growth and popularity.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] Congress authorized the FAA to devise programs to insulate homes near airports.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] While this does not address the external noise, the program has been effective for residential interiors.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] Some of the airports where the technology was first applied were San Francisco International Airport and San Jose International Airport in California.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] A computer model is used which simulates the effects of aircraft noise upon building structures.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] Variations of aircraft type, flight patterns and local meteorology can be studied.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] Then, the benefits of building retrofit strategies such as roof upgrading, window glazing improvement, fireplace baffling, caulking construction seams can be evaluated.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] Noise stages are defined in the US Code of Federal Regulations (CFR) Title 14 Part 36.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] For civil aircraft, the US FAA Stage 1 is the loudest and Stage 4 is the quietest.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] Stage 3 was required for all large jet and turboprop aircraft at US civilian airports from the year 2000, and at least Stage 2 for under 75,000 lb (34 t) MTOW jets until December 31, 2015.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] The US allows both the louder Stage 1 and quiet Stage 2 helicopters.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] The quietest Stage 3 helicopter noise standard became effective on May 5, 2014, and are consistent with ICAO Chapter 8 and Chapter 11.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] At Heathrow, Gatwick and Stansted airports in London, UK and Frankfurt Airport in Germany, night flying restrictions apply to reduce noise exposure at night.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] Modern high bypass turbofans are not only more fuel efficient, but also much quieter than older turbojet and low-bypass turbofan engines.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] On newer engines noise-reducing chevrons further reduce the engine's noise, while on older engines hush kits are used to help mitigate their excessive noise.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] The ability to reduce noise may be limited if engines remain below aircraft's wings.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] NASA expects a cumulative 20–30 dB below Stage 4 limits by 2026–2031, but keeping aircraft noise within airport boundaries requires at least a 40–50 dB reduction.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] Landing gear, wing slats and wing flaps also produce noise and may have to be shielded from the ground with new configurations.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] NASA found that over-wing and mid-fuselage nacelles could reduce noise by 30–40 dB to even 40–50 dB for hybrid wing bodies, which may be essential for open rotors.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] By 2020, helicopter technologies in development plus new procedures could reduce noise levels by 10 dB and noise footprints by 50%, but more advances are needed to preserve or expand heliports.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] Package delivery UAS will need to characterize their noise, establish limits and reduce their impact.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] Usage of satellite-based navigation systems can contribute to noise relief, trials in 2013–14 found, though results were not always beneficial due to concentrating flight paths.
[src:jet-engine-performance/aircraft-noise-pollution] Changing flight angles and flight paths brought some changes in noise relief for some local people.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airfoil] An **airfoil** (American English) or **aerofoil** (British English) is a streamlined body that is capable of generating significantly more lift than drag.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airfoil] Wings, sails and propeller blades are examples of airfoils.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airfoil] Foils which work in a similar way submerged in water are called hydrofoils.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airfoil] When oriented at a suitable angle, a solid body moving through a fluid deflects the passing fluid, resulting in a force on the airfoil in the direction opposite to the deflection.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airfoil] This force is known as an aerodynamic force and can be resolved into two components: lift (perpendicular to the freestream velocity) and drag (parallel to the freestream velocity).
[src:jet-engine-performance/airfoil] The lift on an airfoil is primarily the result of its angle of attack.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airfoil] Most foil shapes require a positive angle of attack to generate lift, but cambered airfoils can generate lift at zero angle of attack.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airfoil] Airfoils have different shapes for different speeds: those for subsonic flight have a rounded leading edge, while those for supersonic flight tend to be slimmer.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airfoil] The deflection of air by an airfoil generates a lower-pressure region above and behind itself.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airfoil] This pressure difference is accompanied by a velocity difference, as explained by Bernoulli's principle, so the resulting flowfield about the airfoil has a higher average velocity on the upper surface than on the lower surface.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airfoil] In some situations (e.g., inviscid potential flow) the lift force can be related directly to the average top/bottom velocity difference without computing the pressure by using the concept of circulation and the Kutta–Joukowski theorem.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airfoil] The wings and stabilizers of fixed-wing aircraft, as well as helicopter rotor blades, are built with airfoil-shaped cross sections.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airfoil] Airfoils are also found in propellers, fans, compressors and turbines.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airfoil] Sails are also airfoils, and the underwater surfaces of sailboats, such as the centerboard, rudder, and keel, are similar in cross-section and operate on the same principles as airfoils.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airfoil] Swimming and flying creatures and even many plants and sessile organisms employ airfoils/hydrofoils, common examples being bird wings, the bodies of fish, and the shape of sand dollars.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airfoil] An airfoil-shaped wing can create downforce on an automobile or other motor vehicle, improving traction.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airfoil] When the wind is obstructed by an object such as a flat plate, a building, or the deck of a bridge, the object will experience drag and also an aerodynamic force perpendicular to the wind.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airfoil] This does not mean the object qualifies as an airfoil.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airfoil] Airfoils are highly-efficient lifting shapes, able to generate more lift than similarly sized flat plates of the same area, and able to generate lift with significantly less drag.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airfoil] Airfoils are used in the design of aircraft, propellers, rotor blades, wind turbines and other applications of aeronautical engineering.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airfoil] A lift and drag curve obtained in wind tunnel testing is shown on the right.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airfoil] The curve represents an airfoil with a positive camber so some lift is produced at zero angle of attack.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airfoil] With increased angle of attack, lift increases in a roughly linear relation, called the *slope* of the lift curve.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airfoil] At about 18 degrees this airfoil stalls, and lift falls off quickly beyond that.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airfoil] The drop in lift can be explained by the action of the upper-surface boundary layer, which separates and greatly thickens over the upper surface at and past the stall angle.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airfoil] The thickened boundary layer's displacement thickness changes the airfoil's effective shape, in particular it reduces its effective camber, which modifies the overall flow field so as to reduce the circulation and the lift.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airfoil] The thicker boundary layer also causes a large increase in pressure drag, so that the overall drag increases sharply near and past the stall point.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airfoil] Airfoil design is a major facet of aerodynamics.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airfoil] Various airfoils serve different flight regimes.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airfoil] Asymmetric airfoils can generate lift at zero angle of attack, while a symmetric airfoil may better suit frequent inverted flight as in an aerobatic airplane.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airfoil] In the region of the ailerons and near a wingtip a symmetric airfoil can be used to increase the range of angles of attack to avoid spin–stall.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airfoil] Thus a large range of angles can be used without boundary layer separation.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airfoil] Subsonic airfoils have a round leading edge, which is naturally insensitive to the angle of attack.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airfoil] The cross section is not strictly circular, however: the radius of curvature is increased before the wing achieves maximum thickness to minimize the chance of boundary layer separation.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airfoil] This elongates the wing and moves the point of maximum thickness back from the leading edge.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airfoil] Supersonic airfoils are much more angular in shape and can have a very sharp leading edge, which is very sensitive to angle of attack.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airfoil] A supercritical airfoil has its maximum thickness close to the leading edge to have a lot of length to slowly shock the supersonic flow back to subsonic speeds.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airfoil] Generally such transonic airfoils and also the supersonic airfoils have a low camber to reduce drag divergence.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airfoil] Modern aircraft wings may have different airfoil sections along the wing span, each one optimized for the conditions in each section of the wing.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airfoil] Movable high-lift devices, flaps and sometimes slats, are fitted to airfoils on almost every aircraft.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airfoil] A trailing edge flap acts similarly to an aileron; however, it, as opposed to an aileron, can be retracted partially into the wing if not used.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airfoil] For many wings, the boundary layer of the air flow close to the upper surface rapidly becomes turbulent past the maximum thickness point, which increases the skin friction drag.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airfoil] A **laminar flow wing** moves the maximum thickness point well back along the chord from a typical 25% chord position from to 60% from the leading edge or more.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airfoil] This maintains smooth laminar flow over a larger percentage of the wing and significantly reduces drag.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airfoil] However, surface contamination will disrupt the boundary layer, making it turbulent.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airfoil] Insects, for example, impacting and sticking onto the wing will cause the loss of wedge shaped regions of laminar flow across the wing's surface.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airfoil] This is a particular problem for aircraft with high take off speeds, since many insects are found near the ground making it unlikely that laminar flow can be sustained into the flight.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airfoil] Gliders have seen widespread uptake of laminar flow airfoils due to their low speeds and need for low drag aerodynamic structures.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airfoil] NASA's research in the 1980s revealed the practicality and usefulness of laminar flow wing designs and opened the way for laminar-flow applications on modern practical aircraft surfaces, from subsonic general aviation aircraft to transonic large transport aircraft, to supersonic designs.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airfoil] Schemes have been devised to define airfoils – an example is the NACA system.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airfoil] Various airfoil generation systems are also used.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airfoil] An example of a general purpose airfoil that finds wide application, and pre–dates the NACA system, is the Clark-Y.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airfoil] Today, airfoils can be designed for specific functions by the use of computer programs.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airfoil] Some important parameters to describe an airfoil's shape are its *camber* and its *thickness*.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airfoil] For example, an airfoil of the NACA 4-digit series such as the NACA 2415 (to be read as 2 – 4 – 15) describes an airfoil with a camber of 0.02 chord located at 0.40 chord, with 0.15 chord of maximum thickness.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airfoil] In two-dimensional flow around a uniform wing of infinite span, the slope of the lift curve is determined primarily by the *trailing edge angle*.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airfoil] The slope is greatest if the angle is zero; and decreases as the angle increases.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airfoil] For a wing of finite span, the aspect ratio of the wing also significantly influences the slope of the curve.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airfoil] As aspect ratio decreases, the slope also decreases.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airfoil] 2. on a cambered airfoil, the aerodynamic center lies exactly one quarter of the chord behind the leading edge, but the position of the center of pressure moves when the angle of attack changes.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airfoil] 3. the slope of the *lift coefficient versus angle of attack* line is $2\pi \!$ units per radian.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airfoil] is the section lift coefficient when the angle of attack is zero.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airfoil] Thin airfoil theory assumes the air is an inviscid fluid so does not account for the stall of the airfoil, which usually occurs at an angle of attack between 10° and 15° for typical airfoils.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airfoil] In the mid-late 2000s, however, a theory predicting the onset of leading-edge stall was proposed by Wallace J.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airfoil] Morris's subsequent refinements contain the details on the current state of theoretical knowledge on the leading-edge stall phenomenon.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airfoil] Morris's theory predicts the critical angle of attack for leading-edge stall onset as the condition at which a global separation zone is predicted in the solution for the inner flow.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airfoil] Morris's theory demonstrates that a subsonic flow about a thin airfoil can be described in terms of an outer region, around most of the airfoil chord, and an inner region, around the nose, that asymptotically match each other.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airfoil] As the flow in the outer region is dominated by classical thin airfoil theory, Morris's equations exhibit many components of thin airfoil theory.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airfoil] In thin airfoil theory, the width of the (2D) airfoil is assumed negligible, and the airfoil itself replaced with a 1D blade along its camber line, oriented at the angle of attack α.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airfoil] Let the position along the blade be x, ranging from 0 at the wing's front to c at the trailing edge; the camber of the airfoil, *dy*⁄*dx*, is assumed sufficiently small that one need not distinguish between x and position relative to the fuselage.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airfoil] The flow across the airfoil generates a circulation around the blade, which can be modeled as a vortex sheet of position-varying strength γ(*x*).
[src:jet-engine-performance/airfoil] The Kutta condition implies that γ(*c*)=0, but the strength is singular at the bladefront, with γ(*x*)∝1⁄√*x* for *x* ≈ 0.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airfoil] From the Biot–Savart law, the vorticity γ(*x*) produces a flow field $w(x)={\frac {1}{2\pi }}\int _{0}^{c}{\frac {\gamma (x')}{x-x'}}\,dx'{\text{,}}$ oriented normal to the airfoil at x.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airfoil] Since the airfoil is an impermeable surface, the flow $w(x)$ must balance an inverse flow from V.
[src:jet-engine-performance/airfoil] By the small-angle approximation, V is inclined at angle α-*dy*⁄*dx* relative to the blade at position x, and the normal component is correspondingly (α-*dy*⁄*dx*)*V*.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] American Airlines and American Eagle operate out of ten hubs, anchored by Dallas Fort Worth International Airport (DFW), the airline's largest.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] Charlotte Douglas International Airport (CLT) follows as the second-largest hub, serving as a primary gateway for Southeast and transatlantic travel.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] The airline serves more than 200 million passengers annually, and averages more than 500,000 daily.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] As of 2024, the company employs 103,440 staff members.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] The earliest predecessor company of American Airlines to commence operations was Robertson Aircraft Corporation, which began mail flights on April 15, 1926.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] American Airlines was started in 1930 as a union of more than eighty small airlines.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] The two organizations from which American Airlines originated were Robertson Aircraft Corporation and Colonial Air Transport.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] The former was first created in Missouri in 1921, with both being merged in 1929 into holding company The Aviation Corporation.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] This, in turn, was made in 1930 into an operating company and rebranded as **American Airways**.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] In 1934, when new laws and attrition of mail contracts forced many airlines to reorganize, the corporation redid its routes into a connected system and was renamed American Airlines.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] The airline fully developed its international business between 1970 and 2000.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] It purchased Trans World Airlines in 2001.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] American had a direct role in the development of the Douglas DC-3, which resulted from a marathon telephone call from American Airlines CEO C.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] Smith to Douglas Aircraft Company founder Donald Wills Douglas Sr., when Smith persuaded a reluctant Douglas to design a sleeper aircraft based on the DC-2 to replace American's Curtiss Condor II biplanes.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] (The existing DC-2's cabin was 66 inches (1.7 m) wide, too narrow for side-by-side berths.) Douglas agreed to proceed with development only after Smith informed him of American Airline's intention to purchase 20 aircraft.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] The prototype DST (Douglas Sleeper Transport) first flew on December 17, 1935, the 32nd anniversary of the Wright Brothers' flight at Kitty Hawk, North Carolina.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] Its cabin was 92 in (2.3 m) wide, and a version with 21 seats instead of the 14–16 sleeping berths of the DST was given the designation DC-3.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] There was no prototype DC-3; the first DC-3 built followed seven DSTs off the production line and was delivered to American Airlines.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] American Airlines inaugurated passenger service on June 26, 1936, with simultaneous flights from Newark, New Jersey, and Chicago, Illinois.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] American also had a direct role in the development of the DC-10, which resulted from a specification from American Airlines to manufacturers in 1966 to offer a widebody aircraft that was smaller than the Boeing 747, but capable of flying similar long-range routes from airports with shorter runways.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] McDonnell Douglas responded with the DC-10 trijet shortly after the two companies' merger.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] On February 19, 1968, the president of American Airlines, George A.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] McDonnell of McDonnell Douglas announced American's intention to acquire the DC-10.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] American Airlines ordered 25 DC-10s in its first order.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] The DC-10 made its first flight on August 29, 1970, and received its type certificate from the FAA on July 29, 1971.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] On August 5, 1971, the DC-10 entered commercial service with American Airlines on a round-trip flight between Los Angeles and Chicago.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] In 2011, due to a downturn in the airline industry, American Airlines' parent company, the AMR Corporation, filed for bankruptcy protection.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] In 2013, American Airlines merged with US Airways but kept the American Airlines name, as it was the better-recognized brand internationally; the combination of the two airlines resulted in the creation of the largest airline in the United States, and ultimately the world.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] In December 2023, the company was added to the Dow Jones Sustainability World Index, and was named to the index for a second consecutive year in December 2024.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] American Eagle is the brand for regional airline flights operated for American Airlines, encompassing flights by wholly owned affiliates Envoy Air, PSA Airlines, and Piedmont Airlines, as well as third-party carriers Republic Airways and SkyWest Airlines.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] These regional carriers serve smaller markets, facilitating connections to American Airlines hubs, and supporting operations in mainline markets.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] All American Eagle carriers share similar logos, uniforms, and aircraft paint schemes as American Airlines’ mainline operations.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] In 2023, 46 million passengers flew on American Eagle regional flights, with about 45% connecting to or from mainline flights.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] These flights operate under capacity purchase agreements with both third-party and wholly owned regional carriers, controlling all aspects of marketing, scheduling, ticketing, pricing, and seat inventories.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] American Airlines pays fixed fees for operating specified aircraft and covering certain variable costs, such as fuel, landing fees, and insurance.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] American Airlines has established three joint ventures with fellow Oneworld alliance members, expanding beyond basic codesharing to include coordinated route planning, scheduling, and revenue sharing on jointly operated routes.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] The Atlantic Joint Business covers transatlantic flights with Aer Lingus, British Airways, Finnair and Iberia.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] The Pacific Joint Business encompasses transpacific flights with Japan Airlines.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] A joint venture with Qantas covers routes between the United States, Australia, and New Zealand.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] As of June 2026, the American Airlines fleet consists of 1,030 mainline aircraft, making it the second largest commercial airline fleet in the world.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] The fleet consists of Airbus and Boeing narrow-body aircraft, and Boeing wide-body aircraft.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] American exclusively ordered Boeing aircraft throughout the 2000s until July 20, 2011, when American announced the largest combined aircraft order in history for 260 Airbus A320 family and 200 Boeing 737 aircraft.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] As of October 2025, American has 301 Airbus and Boeing aircraft on order along with 20 orders and 40 options for Boom Overture supersonic aircraft.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] The average age of the American mainline fleet is 14.2 years as of February 2026.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] As of 2024, American Airlines has four maintenance bases: Tulsa International Airport, Pittsburgh International Airport, Dallas Fort Worth International Airport, and Charlotte Douglas International Airport.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] Flagship First is American's international and transcontinental first class product.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] It is offered only on Boeing 777-300ERs and select Airbus A321s, which American designates "A321T".
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] The seats are fully lie-flat and offer direct aisle access with only one on each side of the aisle in each row.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] As with the airline's other premium cabins, Flagship First offers wider food and beverage options, larger seats, and lounge access at certain airports.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] American offers domestic Flagship First service on transcontinental routes between New York–JFK and Los Angeles, New York–JFK and San Francisco, New York-JFK and Santa Ana, Boston and Los Angeles, and Miami and Los Angeles, as well as on the standard domestic route between New York-JFK and Boston.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] The airline will debut new Flagship Suite premium seats and a revamped aircraft interior for its long-haul fleet with fresh deliveries of its Airbus A321XLR and Boeing 787-9 aircraft, beginning in 2024.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] Flagship Business is American's international and transcontinental business class product.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] It is offered on all Boeing 777-200ERs, Boeing 777-300ERs, Boeing 787-8s, and Boeing 787-9s, as well as select Airbus A321s.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] All Flagship Business seats are fully lie-flat.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] The amenities in Flagship Business include complimentary alcoholic/non-alcoholic beverages, multi-course meals, and lounge access.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] First Class is the highest class of service on domestically configured aircraft.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] When such aircraft are used on international services this cabin is branded as business class.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] Seats range from 19–21 inches (48–53 cm) in width and have 37–42 inches (94–107 cm) of pitch.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] Dining options include complimentary alcoholic and non-alcoholic beverages on all flights as well as standard economy snack offerings, enhanced snack basket selections on flights over 500 miles (800 km), and meals on flights 900 miles (1,400 km) or longer.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] Premium Economy is American's economy plus product.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] The cabin debuted on the airline's Boeing 787-9s in late 2016 and is also available on Boeing 777-200s and -300s, and Boeing 787-8s.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] Premium Economy seats are wider than seats in the main cabin (American's economy cabin) and provide more amenities: Premium Economy customers get two free checked bags, priority boarding, and enhanced food and drink service, including free alcohol.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] This product made American Airlines the first U.S. carrier to offer a four-cabin aircraft.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] Main Cabin (economy class) is American's economy product found on all mainline and regional aircraft in its fleet.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] American markets several rows within the main cabin immediately behind Main Cabin Extra as "Main Cabin Preferred", which requires an extra charge to select for those without status.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] Main Cabin Extra seats are located in the front few rows and exit rows of the economy cabin on all aircraft and have additional pitch, complimentary alcoholic beverages and boarding one group ahead of the main cabin.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] It is available on all of the mainline fleet and American Eagle aircraft.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] American also offers Basic Economy, the airline's lowest main cabin fare on many routes.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] Basic Economy consists of a Main Cabin ticket with numerous restrictions, including waiting until check-in for a seat assignment, no upgrades or refunds, and boarding in the last group.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] Originally Basic Economy passengers could only carry a personal item.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] Later, American revised their Basic Economy policies to allow for a carry-on bag.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] In May 2017, American announced it would add more seats to some of its Boeing 737 MAX 8 jets and reduce overall legroom in the basic economy class.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] The last three rows were to lose 2 inches (5.1 cm), going from the current 31 to 29 inches (79 to 74 cm).
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] The remainder of the main cabin was to have 30 inches (76 cm) of legroom.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] This "Project Oasis" seating configuration has since been expanded to all 737 MAX 8s as well as standard Boeing 737-800 and non-transcontinental Airbus A321 jets.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] New Airbus A321neo jets have been delivered with the same configuration.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] This configuration has been considered unpopular with passengers, especially American's frequent flyers, as the new seats have less padding, less legroom, and no seatback entertainment.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] AAdvantage is the frequent flyer program for American Airlines.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] It was launched on May 1, 1981, and remains the largest frequent flyer program, with over 115 million members as of 2021.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] Miles accumulated in the program allow members to redeem tickets, upgrade service class, or obtain free or discounted car rentals, hotel stays, merchandise, or other products and services through partners.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] AAdvantage status corresponds with Oneworld status levels allowing elites to receive reciprocal benefits from American's Oneworld partner airlines.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] AAdvantage co-branded credit cards are also available and offer other benefits.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] Currently cards are issued by CitiCards, a subsidiary of Citigroup in the United States, by several banks including Butterfield Bank and Scotiabank in the Caribbean, and by Banco Santander in Brazil.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] In December 2024, it was announced that American would be cutting ties with Barclays and would instead be rolling members into its partnership with Citigroup starting in 2026.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] AAdvantage allows one-way redemption, starting at 7,500 miles.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] The Admirals Club was conceived by AA president C.R.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] Smith as a marketing promotion shortly after he was made an honorary Texas Ranger.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] Inspired by the Kentucky colonels and other honorary title designations, Smith decided to make particularly valued passengers "admirals" of the "Flagship fleet" (AA called its aircraft "Flagships" at the time).
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] The list of admirals included many celebrities, politicians, and other VIPs, as well as more "ordinary" customers who had been particularly loyal to the airline.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] There was no physical Admirals Club until shortly after the opening of LaGuardia Airport, then known as New York Municipal Airport.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] During the airport's construction, New York Mayor Fiorello LaGuardia had an upper-level lounge for press conferences and business meetings.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] At one such press conference, he noted that the entire terminal was being offered for lease to airline tenants; after a reporter asked whether the lounge would be leased as well, LaGuardia replied that it would, and a vice president of AA immediately offered to lease the premises.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] The airline then procured a liquor license and began operating the lounge as the "Admirals Club" in 1939.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] The second Admirals Club opened at Washington National Airport.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] Because it was illegal to sell alcohol in Virginia at the time, the club contained refrigerators for the use of its members so they could store their liquor at the airport.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] For many years, membership in the Admirals Club (and most other airline lounges) was by the airline's invitation.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] After a passenger sued for discrimination, the club switched to a paid membership program in 1974.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] Though affiliated with the Admirals Club and staffed by many of the same employees, the Flagship Lounge is a separate lounge designed explicitly for customers flying in first class and business class on international flights and transcontinental domestic flights.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] American Airlines, Inc., is publicly traded through its parent company, American Airlines Group Inc., under NASDAQ: AAL Nasdaq: AAL, with a market capitalization of about $11 billion as of 2024.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] American Eagle is a network of six regional carriers that operate under a codeshare and service agreement with American, operating flights to destinations in the United States, Canada, the Caribbean, and Mexico.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] Three of these carriers are independent, and three are subsidiaries of American Airlines Group: Envoy Air Inc., Piedmont Airlines, Inc., and PSA Airlines Inc.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] American Airlines is headquartered across several buildings in Fort Worth, Texas that it calls the "Robert L.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] Crandall Campus" in honor of former president and CEO Robert Crandall.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] The 1,700,000-square-foot (160,000 m2), five-building office complex was designed by Pelli Clarke Pelli Architects.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] The campus is located on 300 acres, adjacent to Dallas/Fort Worth International Airport, American's fortress hub.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] Before it was headquartered in Texas, American Airlines was headquartered at 633 Third Avenue in the Murray Hill area of Midtown Manhattan, New York City.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] In 1979, American moved its headquarters to a site at Dallas/Fort Worth International Airport, which affected up to 1,300 jobs.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] Mayor of New York City Ed Koch described the move as a "betrayal" of New York City.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] American moved to two leased office buildings in Grand Prairie, Texas.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] The airline began leasing the facility from the airport, which owns the facility.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] Following the merger of US Airways and American Airlines, the new company consolidated its corporate headquarters in Fort Worth, abandoning the US Airways headquarters in Phoenix, AZ.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] As of 2015, American Airlines is the corporation with the most significant presence in Fort Worth.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] In 2015, American announced it would build a new headquarters in Fort Worth.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] Groundbreaking began in the spring of 2016, and occupancy was completed in September 2019.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] The airline plans to house 5,000 new workers in the building.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] It will be located on a 41-acre (17 ha) property adjacent to the airline's flight academy and conference and training center, west of Texas State Highway 360, 2 miles (3.2 km) west from the current headquarters.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] The airline will lease 300 acres (120 ha) from Dallas–Fort Worth International Airport, and this area will include the headquarters.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] Construction of the new headquarters began after the demolition of the Sabre facility, previously on the site.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] The airline considered developing a new headquarters in Irving, Texas, on the old Texas Stadium site, before deciding to keep the headquarters in Fort Worth.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] In 1931, an American employee, Goodrich Murphy designed the AA logo as an entry in a logo contest.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] The eagle in the logo was copied from a Scottish hotel brochure.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] The initial logo contained large red letters on either side of the eagle, enclosed in a double red and white circle against a blue background.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] This initial logo laid the foundation for the visual identity of the airline for 80 years.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] The logo was modified for the first time in 1946, eliminating the red and white circles and making the eagle more prominent.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] The corporate name was standardized in a sans-serif font in italic capital letters.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] The visual identity was again updated in 1962 with the addition of a lighter red as an accent color and a medium grey replacing the grayish dark blue.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] The logo was enclosed in a red circle, the eagle designed to be more figurative, and the double A's compacted.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] In 1967 with the airline expanding its fleet and competing for new routes, a review of its visual identity was initiated. in 1968, under the direction of Massimo Vignelli (founding partner of Unimark) a new identity program was created.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] According to Vignelli, the approach was "not styling but reductionist based on the notion of timelessness." A blue stylized bird (created by Henry Dreyfuss) was placed between Unimark's AA symbols, a design which endured until 2013.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] Thirty years later, in 1997, American Airlines was able to make its logo Internet-compatible by buying the domain AA.com.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] *AA* is also American's two-letter IATA airline designator.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] On January 17, 2013, American launched a new rebranding and marketing campaign with FutureBrand dubbed "A New American".
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] This included a new logo, which includes elements of the 1967 logo.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] American Airlines faced difficulty obtaining copyright registration for their 2013 logo.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] On June 3, 2016, American Airlines sought to register it with the United States Copyright Office, but in October of that year, the Copyright Office ruled that the logo was ineligible for copyright protection, as it did not pass the threshold of originality, and was thus in the public domain.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] American requested that the Copyright Office reconsider.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] Still, on January 8, 2018, the Copyright Office affirmed its initial determination.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] After American Airlines submitted additional materials, the Copyright Office reversed its decision on December 7, 2018, and ruled that the logo contained enough creativity to merit copyright protection.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] American's early liveries varied widely, but a standard livery was adopted in the 1930s, featuring an eagle painted on the fuselage.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] The eagle became a symbol of the company and inspired the name of American Eagle Airlines.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] Propeller aircraft featured an international orange lightning bolt running down the length of the fuselage, which was replaced by a simpler orange stripe with the introduction of jets.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] In the late 1960s, American commissioned designer Massimo Vignelli to develop a new livery.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] The original design called for a red, white, and blue stripe on the fuselage and a simple "AA" logo, without an eagle, on the tail; instead, Vignelli created a highly stylized eagle, which remained the company's logo until January 16, 2013.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] On January 17, 2013, American unveiled a new livery.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] Before then, American had been the only major U.S. airline to leave most of its aircraft surfaces unpainted.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] Smith would not say he liked painted aircraft and refused to use any liveries that involved painting the entire plane.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] Robert "Bob" Crandall later justified the distinctive natural metal finish by noting that less paint reduced the aircraft's weight, thus saving fuel costs.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] In January 2013, American launched a new rebranding and marketing campaign dubbed "The New American." In addition to a new logo, American Airlines introduced a new livery for its fleet.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] The airline calls the new livery and branding "a clean and modern update".
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] The current design features an abstract American flag on the tail, along with a silver-painted fuselage, as a throw-back to the old livery.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] The new design was painted by Leading Edge Aviation Services in California.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] Later in January 2013, Bloomberg asked the designer of the 1968 American Airlines logo (Massimo Vignelli) on his opinion over the rebranding.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] Vignelli replied "now they have something other than Helvetica that's not as good or as powerful", adding that "it has no sense of permanence".
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] In the end, American let their employees decide the new livery's fate.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] On an internal website for employees, American posted two options, one the new livery and one a modified version of the old livery.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] All of the American Airlines Group employees (including US Airways and other affiliates) were able to vote.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] American ultimately decided to keep the new look.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] Parker announced that American would keep a US Airways and America West heritage aircraft in the fleet, with plans to add a heritage TWA aircraft and a heritage American plane with the old livery.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] As of September 2019, American has heritage aircraft for Piedmont, PSA, America West, US Airways, Reno Air, TWA, Allegheny, and AirCal in their fleet.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] They also have two AA branded heritage 737-800 aircraft, an AstroJet N905NN, and the polished aluminum livery used from 1967 to 2013, N921NN.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] American, both before and after the merger with US Airways, has consistently performed poorly in rankings.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] *The Wall Street Journal'*s annual airline rankings have ranked American as the worst or second-worst U.S. carrier for ten of the past twelve years, and in the bottom three of U.S. airlines for at least the past twelve years.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] The airline has persistently performed poorly in the areas of losing checked luggage and bumping passengers due to oversold flights.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] In September 2024, the Association of Professional Flight Attendants ratified a five-year contract that included immediate wage increases of up to 20.5% and $514 million in retroactive pay, the first contract to include boarding pay for a unionized cabin crew in the United States.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] In January 2025, the TWU-IAM alliance reached a two-year contract extension covering approximately 34,000 ground workers, with raises of 18 to 26 percent.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] On February 9, 2026, the APFA board of directors issued a unanimous vote of no confidence in CEO Robert Isom, the first such action in the union's history.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] In 1942, American Airlines established Sky Chefs, a wholly owned subsidiary, as a catering company to serve their fleet.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] In 1986, Sky Chefs was sold to Toronto-based Onex Capital Corporation for $170 million.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] Sky Chefs became a subsidiary of Onex Food Services Inc.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] Since 2001, it has been fully owned by the LSG Group.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] In the late-1960s, American Airlines established the Flagship Hotels chain as a subsidiary of Sky Chefs.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] On July 21, 1972, American Airlines leased four hotels from the Loews Corporation, three of them branded as Americana Hotels, for a period of thirty years.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] American merged the hotels with their Flagship Hotels, and rebranded the entire chain as Americana Hotels.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] In 1980, American Airlines sold Americana Hotels to Bass Brothers Enterprises of Fort Worth, Texas.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] Between October 1993 to July 1998, American Airlines was repeatedly cited for using high-sulfur fuel in motor vehicles at 10 major airports around the country, a violation of the Clean Air Act.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] In 1981, as a means of creating revenue in a period of loss-making, American Airlines offered a lifetime pass of unlimited travel for the initial cost of $250,000.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] This entitled the pass holder to fly anywhere in the world without paying any subsequent fare.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] However, after some time, the airline realized they were making losses on the tickets, with the ticketholders costing them up to $1 million each.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] Ticketholders were booking large numbers of flights with some ticketholders flying interstate for lunch or flying to London multiple times a month.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] AA raised the cost of the lifetime pass to $3 million, and then finally stopped offering it in 2003.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] AA then used litigation to cancel two of the lifetime offers, saying the passes "had been terminated due to fraudulent activity".
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] On October 24, 2017, the NAACP issued a travel advisory for American Airlines urging African Americans to "exercise caution" when traveling with the airline.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] The NAACP issued the advisory after four incidents.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] In one incident, a black woman was moved from first class to coach while her white traveling companion was allowed to remain in first class.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] In another incident, a black man was forced to give up his seats after being confronted by two unruly white passengers.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] According to the NAACP, while they did receive complaints on other airlines, most of their complaints in the year before their advisory were on American Airlines.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] In July 2018, the NAACP lifted their travel advisory saying that American has made improvements to mitigate discrimination and unsafe treatment of African Americans.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] In October 2024, the United States Department of Transportation imposed a $50 million penalty on American Airlines for violations of federal disability protection laws between 2019 and 2023, the largest such penalty ever assessed against an airline.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] The violations included unsafe physical assistance to wheelchair users and mishandling of thousands of wheelchairs.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] Of the $50 million, half was payable to the U.S.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] Treasury and half credited toward remediation investments including a wheelchair tracking system and additional staff at hub airports.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] In 1999, American Airlines sued Allied Pilots Association for $45.5 million over damages due to strike action, one of the largest fines ever levied against a trade union.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] In January 2020, the Allied Pilots Association filed a lawsuit to stop flights between the United States and China over concerns about COVID-19.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] The Association of Professional Flight Attendants supported the court action.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] At the time, COVID-19 was mostly contained to China and had not reached pandemic status yet.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] Because of this action, American Airlines suspended their flights the following day.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] As of January 2025, American Airlines has had almost 60 aircraft hull losses, beginning with the crash of a Ford 5-AT-C Trimotor in August 1931.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] Of the hull losses, most were propeller-driven aircraft, including three Lockheed L-188 Electra aircraft (of which one, the crash in 1959 of Flight 320, resulted in fatalities).
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] The two accidents with the highest fatalities in both the airline's and U.S. aviation history were Flight 191 in 1979 and Flight 587 in 2001.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] Out of the 17 hijackings of American Airlines flights, two aircraft were hijacked and destroyed in the September 11 attacks: Flight 11 crashed into the North Tower of the World Trade Center and Flight 77 crashed into the Pentagon.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] Flight 11, which is responsible for an estimated 1,700 deaths, is the deadliest air crash in the history of aviation.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] Two training flight accidents have occurred in which the crew was killed and six that resulted in no fatalities.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] Another four jet aircraft have been written off due to incidents while they were parked between flights or while undergoing maintenance.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] American Airlines reported total CO2e emissions (direct and indirect) for the twelve months ending December 31, 2020, at 20,092 Kt (-21,347 /-51.5% y-o-y).
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] The company aims to achieve net zero carbon emissions by 2050.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] American Airlines emitted roughly between 40,000,000-45,000,000 metric tons of carbon dioxide equivalents (MTCDE) annually between 2014-2019.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] In 2020, emissions declined to 20,000,000 MTCDE as a result of travel restrictions during the COVID-19 pandemic, and have since increased back up to 40,000,000 MTCDE in 2023.
[src:jet-engine-performance/american-airlines] According to Bloomberg terminal data, American Airlines receives an overall Environmental Social Governance (ESG) score of 5.82, which is ranked as a “leading” score compared to competitors in the industry.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] An **axial compressor** is a type of gas compressor that continuously pressurizes a working fluid.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] It is a rotating, airfoil-based device in which the fluid flows primarily in one direction parallel to the axis of rotation.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] This distinguishes axial compressors from other types of rotating compressors, such as centrifugal compressors, axi-centrifugal compressors, and mixed-flow compressors, in which the fluid flowing includes a significant radial component directed outward from the axis of rotation.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] The rotor blades exert torque on the fluid, increasing its energy as it passes through the compressor.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] The stationary blades, or stators, slow the fluid, converting the circumferential component of flowing into pressure.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] Compressors are typically driven by an electric motor, a steam turbine, or a gas turbine.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] Axial flow compressors produce a continuous flow of compressed gas.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] They exhibit high efficiency and large mass flow rate in relation to the size of their cross-section.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] They are more intricate and expensive relative to other designs, requiring several rows of airfoils to achieve a large pressure rise.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] Axial compressors are integral to the design of large gas turbines such as jet engines, high speed ship engines, and small scale power stations.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] They are also used in industrial applications such as large volume air separation plants, blast furnace air, fluid catalytic cracking air, and propane dehydrogenation.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] Additionally, due to their performance and operability across the flight envelope (safe operational limits for an aircraft), they are widely used in aerospace applications.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] Axial compressors consist of alternating rows of rotating and stationary airfoils.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] The rotating airfoils, or rotors, are mounted on a rotating drum, which is driven by a central shaft.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] The stationary airfoils, known as vanes or stators, are mounted to a tubular casing.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] One row of rotors and one row of stators together form a stage.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] The rotors impart kinetic energy to the working fluid, increasing its velocity in the axial and circumferential directions.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] The stators convert the increased kinetic energy into static pressure through diffusion and redirect the flow direction of the fluid to prepare it for the rotor blades of the next stage.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] The area between the rotor drum and casing decreases along the flow direction to maintain an optimum Mach number as the fluid is compressed.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] Rotor passages can be designed to achieve diffusive pressure rise, leading to a higher pressure rise per stage.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] The ratio of pressure rise in the rotor to the total pressure rise of the stage is known as the degree of reaction.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] The increase in pressure produced by a single stage is limited by the relative velocity between the rotor and the fluid, and the turning and diffusion capabilities of the airfoils.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] A typical stage in a commercial compressor will produce a pressure increase of between 15% and 60% (pressure ratios of 1.15–1.6) at design conditions with a polytropic efficiency in the region of 90–95%.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] To achieve different pressure ratios, axial compressors are designed with different numbers of stages and rotational speeds.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] As a rule of thumb, it can be assumed that each stage in a given compressor has the same temperature rise (ΔT).
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] Therefore, at the entry, temperature (Tstage) to each stage must increase progressively through the compressor and the ratio (Delta T)/(Tstage) entry must decrease, thus implying a progressive reduction in stage pressure ratio through the unit.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] Hence the rear stage develops a significantly lower pressure ratio than the first stage.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] Higher stage pressure ratios are also possible if the relative velocity between fluid and rotors is supersonic, but this is achieved at the expense of efficiency and operability.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] Such compressors, with stage pressure ratios of over 2, are only used where minimizing the compressor size, weight or complexity is critical, such as in military jets.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] The airfoil profiles are optimized and matched for specific velocities and turning.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] Although compressors can be run at other conditions with different flows, speeds, or pressure ratios, this can result in an efficiency penalty or even a partial or complete breakdown in flow (known as compressor stall and pressure surge respectively).
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] Thus, a practical limit on the number of stages, and the overall pressure ratio, comes from the interaction of the different stages when required to work away from the design conditions.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] These "off-design" conditions can be mitigated to a certain extent by providing some flexibility in the compressor.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] This is achieved normally through the use of adjustable stators or with valves that can bleed fluid from the main flow between stages (inter-stage bleed).
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] Modern jet engines use a series of compressors, running at different speeds; to supply air at around 40:1 pressure ratio for combustion with sufficient flexibility for all flight conditions.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] The law of moment of momentum states that the sum of the moments of external forces acting on a fluid which is temporarily occupying the control volume is equal to the net change of angular momentum flux through the control volume.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] The swirling fluid enters the control volume at radius, $r_{1}\,$ , with tangential velocity, $V_{w1}\,$ , and leaves at radius, $r_{2}\,$ , with tangential velocity, $V_{w2}\,$ .
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] are the absolute velocities at the inlet and outlet respectively.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] are the axial flow velocities at the inlet and outlet respectively.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] are the swirl velocities at the inlet and outlet respectively.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] are the blade-relative velocities at the inlet and outlet respectively.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] Axial compressor performance is shown on a compressor map, also known as a characteristic, by plotting pressure ratio and efficiency against corrected mass flow at different values of corrected compressor speed.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] Axial compressors, particularly near their design point are usually amenable to analytical treatment, and a good estimate of their performance can be made before they are first run on a rig.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] The compressor map shows the complete running range, i.e. off-design, of the compressor from ground idle to its highest corrected rotor speed, which for a civil engine may occur at top-of-climb, or, for a military combat engine, at take-off on a cold day.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] Not shown is the sub-idle performance region needed for analysing normal ground and in-flight windmill start behaviour.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] Stage pressure ratio against flow rate is lower than for a no-loss stage as shown.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] Losses are due to blade friction, flow separation, unsteady flow and vane-blade spacing.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] The performance of a compressor is defined according to its design.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] But in actual practice, the operating point of the compressor deviates from the design point; this is known as *off-design operation*.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] The value of $(\tan \beta _{2}+\tan \alpha _{1})\,$ doesn't change for a wide range of operating points till stalling.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] Also $\alpha _{1}=\alpha _{3}\,$ because of minor change in air angle at rotor and stator, where $\alpha _{3}\,$ is diffuser blade angle.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] for positive values of J, slope of the curve is negative and vice versa.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] There are multiple modes of instability an axial compressor could undergo.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] Edward Greitzer used a Helmholtz resonator type of compression system model to predict the transient response of a compression system after a small perturbation superimposed on a steady operating condition.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] He found a non-dimensional parameter which predicted which mode of compressor instability, rotating stall or surge, would result.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] The parameter used the rotor speed, the Helmholtz resonator frequency of the system, and an "effective length" of the compressor duct.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] These produced a critical value which predicted either rotating stall or surge where the slope of pressure ratio against flow changed from negative to positive.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] In the plot of pressure-flow rate, the line separating graph between two regions – unstable and stable – is known as the **surge line**.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] This line is formed by joining surge points at different rotational speeds.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] Surging is the unstable flow in axial compressors due to complete breakdown of the steady through flow.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] This phenomenon affects the performance of compressor and is undesirable.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] The following explanation for surging refers to running a compressor at a constant speed on a rig and gradually reducing the exit area by closing a valve.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] What happens, i.e. crossing the surge line, is caused by the compressor trying to deliver air, still running at the same speed, to a higher exit pressure.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] Suppose the initial operating point *D* ( ${\dot {m}},P_{D}\,$ ) at some rotational speed *N*.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] On decreasing the flow-rate at same rotational speed along the characteristic curve by partial closing of the valve, the pressure in the pipe increases which will be taken care by increase in input pressure at the compressor.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] With further increase in pressure up to point *P* (surge point), compressor pressure will increase.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] Further moving towards left keeping rotational speed constant, pressure in pipe will increase but compressor pressure will decrease leading to back air flow towards the compressor.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] Due to this back flow, pressure in pipe will decrease because this unequal pressure condition cannot stay for a long period of time.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] Though valve position is set for lower flow rate say point *G* but compressor will work according to normal stable operation point say *E*, so path *E*–*F*–*P*–*G*–*E* will be followed leading to breakdown of flow, hence pressure in the compressor falls further to point *H*( $P_{H}\,$ ).
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] This increase and decrease of pressure in pipe will occur repeatedly in pipe and compressor following the cycle *E*–*F*–*P*–*G*–*H*–*E* also known as the surge cycle.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] This phenomenon will cause vibrations in the whole machine and may lead to mechanical failure.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] That is why left portion of the curve from the surge point is called unstable region and may cause damage to the machine.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] So the recommended operation range is on the right side of the surge line.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] Stall is a phenomenon affecting the performance of the compressor whereby flow separation occurs at the compressor blades, leading to reduced compression and a drop in engine power.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] An analysis is made of rotating stall in compressors of many stages, finding conditions under which a flow distortion can occur which is steady in a traveling reference frame, even though upstream total and downstream static pressure are constant.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] In the compressor, a pressure-rise hysteresis is assumed.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] Two types of stall are distinguished: *positive stall,* where flow separation occurs on the suction side of the blade, and *negative stall,* where it occurs on the pressure side.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] In practice, negative stall is negligible compared to positive stall as flow separation is least likely to occur on the pressure side of the blade.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] In a multi-stage compressor, at the high pressure stages, axial velocity is very small.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] Stalling value decreases with a small deviation from the design point causing stall near the hub and tip regions whose size increases with decreasing flow rates.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] They grow larger at very low flow rate and affect the entire blade height.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] Non-uniformity of air flow in the rotor blades may disturb local air flow in the compressor without upsetting it.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] The compressor continues to work normally but with reduced compression.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] Thus, rotating stall decreases the effectiveness of the compressor.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] In a rotor with blades moving say towards right.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] Let some blades receives flow at higher incidence, this blade will stop positively.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] It creates obstruction in the passage between the blade to its left and itself.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] Thus the left blade will receive the flow at higher incidence and the blade to its right with decreased incidence.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] The left blade will experience more stall while the blade to its right will experience lesser stall.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] Towards the right stalling will decrease whereas it will increase towards its left.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] Movement of the rotating stall can be observed depending upon the chosen reference frame.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] From an energy exchange point of view axial compressors are reversed turbines.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] Steam-turbine designer Charles Algernon Parsons, for example, recognized that a turbine which produced work by virtue of a fluid's static pressure (i.e. a reaction turbine) could have its action reversed to act as an air compressor, calling it a turbo compressor or pump.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] His rotor and stator blading described in one of his patents had little or no camber although in some cases the blade design was based on propeller theory.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] The machines, driven by steam turbines, were used for industrial purposes such as supplying air to blast furnaces.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] Parsons supplied the first commercial axial flow compressor for use in a lead smelter in 1901.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] Parsons' machines had low efficiencies, later attributed to blade stall, and were soon replaced with more efficient centrifugal compressors.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] Brown Boveri & Cie produced "reversed turbine" compressors, driven by gas turbines, with blading derived from aerodynamic research which were more efficient than centrifugal types when pumping large flow rates of 40,000 ft3/min (19 m3/s) at pressures up to 45 psi (310 kPa).
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] Because early axial compressors were not efficient enough a number of papers in the early 1920s claimed that a practical axial-flow turbojet engine would be impossible to construct.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] Griffith published a seminal paper in 1926, noting that the reason for the poor performance was that existing compressors used flat blades and were essentially "flying stalled".
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] He showed that the use of airfoils instead of the flat blades would increase efficiency to the point where a practical jet engine was a real possibility.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] He concluded the paper with a basic diagram of such an engine, which included a second turbine that was used to power a propeller.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] Although Griffith was well known due to his earlier work on metal fatigue and stress measurement, little work appears to have started as a direct result of his paper.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] The only obvious effort was a test-bed compressor built by Hayne Constant, Griffith's colleague at the Royal Aircraft Establishment.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] Other early jet efforts, notably those of Frank Whittle and Hans von Ohain, were based on the more robust and better understood centrifugal compressor which was widely used in superchargers.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] Griffith had seen Whittle's work in 1929 and dismissed it, noting a mathematical error, and going on to claim that the frontal size of the engine would make it useless on a high-speed aircraft.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] Real work on axial-flow engines started in the late 1930s, in several efforts that all started at about the same time.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] In England, Hayne Constant reached an agreement with the steam turbine company Metropolitan-Vickers (Metrovick) in 1937, starting their turboprop effort based on the Griffith design in 1938.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] In 1940, after the successful run of Whittle's centrifugal-flow design, their effort was re-designed as a pure jet, the Metrovick F.2.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] In the United States, both Lockheed and General Electric were awarded contracts in 1941 to develop axial-flow engines, the former a pure jet, the latter a turboprop.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] Northrop also started their own project to develop a turboprop, which the US Navy eventually contracted in 1943.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] Westinghouse also entered the race in 1942, their project proving to be the only successful one of the US efforts, later becoming the J30.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] As Griffith had originally noted in 1929, the large frontal size of the centrifugal compressor caused it to have higher drag than the narrower axial-flow type.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] Additionally the axial-flow design could improve its compression ratio simply by adding additional stages and making the engine slightly longer.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] In the centrifugal-flow design the compressor itself had to be larger in diameter, which was much more difficult to fit properly into a thin and aerodynamic aircraft fuselage (although not dissimilar to the profile of radial engines already in widespread use).
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] On the other hand, centrifugal-flow designs remained much less complex (the major reason they "won" in the race to flying examples) and therefore have a role in places where size and streamlining are not so important.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] In the jet engine application, the compressor faces a wide variety of operating conditions.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] On the ground at high power settings the inlet pressure is high, inlet speed zero, and the compressor spun at a variety of speeds as the power is applied.
[src:jet-engine-performance/axial-compressor] Once in flight the inlet pressure drops, but the inlet speed increases (due to the forward motion of the aircraft) to recover some of this pressure, and the compressor tends to run at a single speed for long periods of time.
